// MedMasters: Dermatology - JCAT/FCPS Part 1 Medicine
// 250 MCQs - First Aid for USMLE Step 1 + Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine
(function(){
  if(!window.MM) window.MM={};
  window.MM['med_p2_derma'] = [
    {q:'The outermost protective barrier preventing transepidermal water loss is primarily formed by',o:['Stratum spinosum','Stratum basale','Stratum corneum','Dermis'],a:2,e:`Stratum corneum is the outermost epidermal layer; its keratin and lipid lamellae form the barrier preventing transepidermal water loss and external pathogen entry.<br><br>It contains anucleate corneocytes embedded in cholesterol, ceramides, and free fatty acids. Disruption of this barrier underlies eczema, ichthyosis, and dehydration in burns.<br><br>Stratum basale (option A) is the proliferative layer at the base; stratum spinosum (option B) provides mechanical strength via desmosomes; dermis (option D) lies beneath the epidermis and provides structural support, not the barrier.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A child with albinism lacks melanin due to defect in melanin synthesis from tyrosine. The responsible cell type is',o:['Melanocyte','Merkel cell','Langerhans cell','Keratinocyte'],a:0,e:`Melanocytes synthesise melanin from tyrosine via tyrosinase; in albinism, defective tyrosinase activity or melanin synthesis produces hypopigmented skin, hair, and eyes despite normal melanocyte count.<br><br>Melanocytes reside in the stratum basale and transfer melanosomes to keratinocytes through dendritic processes. Skin colour reflects melanosome size and distribution, not melanocyte count between individuals.<br><br>Merkel cells (option B) are mechanoreceptors for touch; Langerhans cells (option C) are antigen-presenting cells of bone marrow origin; keratinocytes (option D) form the bulk of the epidermis and produce keratin.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Which layer provides mechanical strength via desmosomes giving “spiny” appearance?',o:['Stratum granulosum','Stratum lucidum','Stratum spinosum','Stratum corneum'],a:2,e:`Stratum spinosum provides epidermal mechanical strength through abundant desmosomes; the spiny appearance on light microscopy reflects desmosomal connections between adjacent keratinocytes.<br><br>Desmosomes link cytokeratin filaments across cells, distributing mechanical force. Pemphigus vulgaris autoantibodies target desmoglein-3, breaking these junctions and producing intraepidermal blisters.<br><br>Stratum granulosum (option A) contains keratohyalin granules; stratum lucidum (option B) is found only in thick skin; stratum corneum (option D) is the outermost protective layer of dead corneocytes.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with blistering disease shows separation just above basement membrane. This junction is located between',o:['Dermis and subcutaneous tissue','Epidermis and dermis','Stratum spinosum and granulosum','Stratum granulosum and corneum'],a:1,e:`Separation just above the basement membrane lies between the epidermis and dermis; this dermo-epidermal junction is anchored by hemidesmosomes and basement membrane components.<br><br>Bullous pemphigoid autoantibodies target hemidesmosome proteins (BP180, BP230), producing tense subepidermal blisters. Dystrophic epidermolysis bullosa involves type VII collagen anchoring fibrils.<br><br>Dermis-subcutaneous junction (option A) lies deeper; stratum spinosum-granulosum (option C) is intraepidermal; stratum granulosum-corneum (option D) is also intraepidermal, all distinct from dermo-epidermal cleavage.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Main protein providing tensile strength in dermis',o:['Collagen','Actin','Keratin','Elastin'],a:0,e:`Collagen, predominantly type I, provides tensile strength in the dermis; bundles run parallel to skin tension lines and resist mechanical loading throughout adult life.<br><br>Type I collagen accounts for over 80 percent of dermal collagen, with type III contributing the remainder. Fibroblasts synthesise collagen, and ageing reduces collagen production with thinning skin.<br><br>Actin (option B) is intracellular cytoskeletal protein; keratin (option C) is in epidermal keratinocytes; elastin (option D) provides elasticity but not tensile strength, working alongside collagen in the dermal matrix.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Langerhans cells originate from',o:['Keratinocyte lineage','Neural crest','Mesenchyme','Bone marrow'],a:3,e:`Langerhans cells originate from bone marrow precursors; they migrate to the epidermis where they function as professional antigen-presenting cells linking innate and adaptive immunity.<br><br>These dendritic cells contain tennis-racket-shaped Birbeck granules. They capture antigens, migrate to regional lymph nodes, and present to T lymphocytes, initiating cutaneous immune responses.<br><br>Keratinocyte lineage (option A) produces keratin; neural crest (option B) gives rise to melanocytes and sensory ganglia; mesenchyme (option C) forms dermis and connective tissues, distinct from haematopoietic origin.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Touch receptors associated with hair follicles are',o:['Meissner corpuscles','Hair root plexus','Pacinian corpuscles','Free nerve endings'],a:1,e:`Hair root plexus surrounds hair follicles and detects movement of hair shafts; light deflection of hair triggers neural firing, providing sensitive touch information about external contact.<br><br>These free nerve ending networks wrap the follicle below the sebaceous gland. They are particularly dense in vibrissae and contribute to detecting low-amplitude air movement and grooming sensations.<br><br>Meissner corpuscles (option A) detect fine touch in glabrous skin; Pacinian corpuscles (option C) detect deep pressure and vibration; free nerve endings (option D) detect pain and temperature, not hair movement specifically.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Which gland produces body odor after bacterial action during puberty?',o:['Ceruminous gland','Sebaceous gland','Apocrine gland','Eccrine gland'],a:2,e:`Apocrine glands produce viscous secretion that becomes odorous after bacterial action; located in axillae, groin, and areolae, they become functional at puberty under hormonal influence.<br><br>Apocrine secretion is initially odourless; resident skin bacteria metabolise lipid and protein components into volatile compounds producing characteristic body odour. Antiperspirants reduce eccrine output rather than apocrine activity.<br><br>Ceruminous glands (option A) produce earwax in the external auditory canal; sebaceous glands (option B) secrete sebum; eccrine glands (option D) secrete watery sweat for thermoregulation throughout the body.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Vitamin D synthesis in skin requires',o:['Ultraviolet B radiation','Infrared radiation','Ultraviolet A radiation','Visible light'],a:0,e:`Vitamin D synthesis in skin requires ultraviolet B radiation (UVB, 290-315 nm); UVB converts 7-dehydrocholesterol in the epidermis to previtamin D3, which thermally isomerises to vitamin D3.<br><br>Subsequent hydroxylations in liver (25-hydroxylation) and kidney (1-alpha-hydroxylation) produce active calcitriol. Sunscreen, dark skin, and northern latitudes reduce cutaneous vitamin D synthesis substantially.<br><br>Infrared radiation (option B) generates heat; UVA radiation (option C) penetrates deeper and contributes to ageing and DNA damage; visible light (option D) is responsible for vision and circadian rhythm, not vitamin D synthesis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A newborn has shiny translucent skin due to underdeveloped layer rich in keratohyalin granules. This layer is',o:['Stratum basale','Stratum spinosum','Stratum corneum','Stratum granulosum'],a:3,e:`Stratum granulosum contains keratohyalin granules; in newborns the layer is underdeveloped, producing the shiny translucent skin appearance characteristic of preterm and full-term neonates.<br><br>Keratohyalin granules contain profilaggrin, which is processed to filaggrin and crosslinks keratin filaments during terminal differentiation. The granular layer thickens during the first weeks of life.<br><br>Stratum basale (option A) is proliferative; stratum spinosum (option B) provides mechanical strength via desmosomes; stratum corneum (option C) is the outermost barrier layer of anucleate corneocytes.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Main function of melanocyte dendrites is',o:['Sweat secretion','Keratin production','Transfer melanosomes to keratinocytes','Immune defense'],a:2,e:`Melanocyte dendrites transfer melanosomes containing melanin pigment to surrounding keratinocytes; one melanocyte serves approximately 36 keratinocytes through this dendritic network.<br><br>Melanosomes accumulate over keratinocyte nuclei, forming a supranuclear cap that absorbs UV radiation and shields nuclear DNA from photodamage. Defects in this transfer underlie certain pigmentary disorders.<br><br>Sweat secretion (option A) is the role of eccrine and apocrine glands; keratin production (option B) is by keratinocytes; immune defence (option D) is mediated by Langerhans cells and skin-resident T cells.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Thick skin differs from thin skin by presence of',o:['Stratum lucidum','Sebaceous glands','Hair follicles','Apocrine glands'],a:0,e:`Thick skin (palms and soles) differs from thin skin by the presence of stratum lucidum; this clear layer provides additional mechanical protection for high-friction body surfaces.<br><br>Thick skin lacks hair follicles and sebaceous glands but has abundant eccrine sweat glands and Meissner corpuscles. Stratum corneum is also thicker. Total epidermal thickness reaches 1.5 mm in palms.<br><br>Sebaceous glands (option B) are absent from palms and soles; hair follicles (option C) are also absent there; apocrine glands (option D) localise to axillae and groin, not characterising thick skin specifically.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Pacinian corpuscles detect',o:['Temperature','Pain','Light touch','Vibration and pressure'],a:3,e:`Pacinian corpuscles detect vibration and deep pressure; their onion-like lamellated capsule rapidly transmits high-frequency mechanical deformation to a central afferent nerve ending.<br><br>Pacinian corpuscles localise to deep dermis and subcutaneous tissue, particularly in fingertips, joint capsules, and mesentery. They respond to vibrations between 30 and 500 Hz with rapid adaptation.<br><br>Temperature (option A) is sensed by free nerve endings; pain (option B) is also free-nerve-ending mediated; light touch (option C) is detected by Meissner corpuscles in the dermal papillae of glabrous skin.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Basement membrane zone primarily contains',o:['Tight junctions','Hemidesmosomes','Desmosomes only','Gap junctions'],a:1,e:`Basement membrane zone primarily contains hemidesmosomes; these specialised junctions anchor basal keratinocytes to the underlying lamina densa via integrin and laminin interactions.<br><br>Hemidesmosomes contain BP180 (collagen XVII) and BP230, the targets of bullous pemphigoid autoantibodies. Anchoring fibrils of type VII collagen extend from lamina densa into papillary dermis.<br><br>Tight junctions (option A) seal paracellular spaces in stratum granulosum; desmosomes only (option C) link adjacent keratinocytes; gap junctions (option D) allow ionic communication between cells, not basement membrane attachment.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Sebum secretion is stimulated mainly by',o:['Androgens','Thyroxine','Estrogen','Cortisol'],a:0,e:`Sebum secretion is stimulated mainly by androgens; testosterone is converted by 5-alpha-reductase to dihydrotestosterone (DHT), which drives sebocyte differentiation and lipid synthesis.<br><br>Androgen-sensitive sebaceous glands enlarge at puberty, increasing sebum output. Excess sebum production combined with follicular hyperkeratinisation underlies acne vulgaris pathogenesis in adolescents and young adults.<br><br>Thyroxine (option B) regulates basal metabolic rate; estrogen (option C) tends to reduce sebaceous activity; cortisol (option D) has complex effects but is not the principal driver of sebum production at puberty.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with burns loses thermoregulation due to loss of',o:['Langerhans cells','Melanocytes','Eccrine sweat glands','Hair follicles'],a:2,e:`Burns destroy eccrine sweat glands; loss of these thermoregulatory structures impairs the patient's ability to dissipate heat through evaporation, predisposing to hyperthermia.<br><br>Eccrine glands open directly onto skin surface and produce hypotonic sweat regulated by sympathetic cholinergic fibres. Burn-induced loss reduces evaporative cooling capacity and contributes to thermoregulatory dysfunction.<br><br>Langerhans cells (option A) are immune sentinels; melanocytes (option B) provide pigmentation; hair follicles (option D) contribute to insulation but not active thermoregulation through evaporative cooling like sweat glands.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Keratinocytes originate from',o:['Endoderm','Mesoderm','Neural crest','Ectoderm'],a:3,e:`Keratinocytes originate from ectoderm; the surface ectoderm gives rise to the epidermis and its appendages including hair follicles, sebaceous glands, and sweat glands.<br><br>Neural crest cells (also ectoderm-derived) contribute melanocytes. Mesoderm forms the dermis. The interaction between epidermis and dermis during development establishes regional skin specialisation through reciprocal signalling.<br><br>Endoderm (option A) forms gut and respiratory linings; mesoderm (option B) forms dermis, muscle, and connective tissue; neural crest (option C) gives rise to melanocytes and peripheral nerves but not keratinocytes.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The papillary dermis mainly contains',o:['Adipose tissue','Loose connective tissue','Smooth muscle','Dense collagen bundles'],a:1,e:`Papillary dermis mainly contains loose connective tissue; thin collagen fibres, elastic fibres, ground substance, and capillary loops support epidermal nutrition and sensation.<br><br>The papillary dermis interdigitates with the epidermis through dermal papillae, increasing surface area for nutrient exchange. Meissner corpuscles and Merkel cell complexes provide tactile sensation in this layer.<br><br>Adipose tissue (option A) characterises subcutaneous tissue; smooth muscle (option C) is found in arrector pili and dartos muscle; dense collagen bundles (option D) characterise reticular dermis providing tensile strength.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient feels sharp pain on needle prick due to activation of',o:['Meissner corpuscles','Merkel cells','Pacinian corpuscles','Free nerve endings'],a:3,e:`Sharp pain on needle prick is detected by free nerve endings; A-delta fibres mediate fast, sharp pain while C fibres convey slower, dull, burning pain sensation.<br><br>Free nerve endings extend into the epidermis and dermis without specialised capsules. They also detect temperature extremes and itch. Substance P and CGRP are key neurotransmitters in nociceptive signalling.<br><br>Meissner corpuscles (option A) sense light touch; Merkel cells (option B) sense sustained pressure and texture; Pacinian corpuscles (option C) detect vibration and deep pressure, not nociceptive sharp pain.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Which cells present antigen to T lymphocytes in skin?',o:['Langerhans cells','Melanocytes','Keratinocytes','Fibroblasts'],a:0,e:`Langerhans cells are the principal antigen-presenting cells of the skin; they capture antigens in epidermis, migrate to lymph nodes, and present to naive T lymphocytes.<br><br>These dendritic cells contain tennis-racket-shaped Birbeck granules visible on electron microscopy. They link cutaneous innate immunity with adaptive responses, central to contact dermatitis and graft rejection mechanisms.<br><br>Melanocytes (option B) produce pigment; keratinocytes (option C) form the structural epidermis; fibroblasts (option D) are dermal cells producing collagen, none of which serve professional antigen-presenting functions.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Elastic recoil of skin is mainly due to',o:['Collagen','Keratin','Elastin','Fibrin'],a:2,e:`Elastic recoil of skin is mainly due to elastin; elastic fibres composed of elastin and microfibrillar fibrillin allow skin to return to its original shape after deformation.<br><br>Elastin is synthesised by fibroblasts and crosslinked extensively. Loss of elastin with photoageing produces solar elastosis, characterised by yellowed, thickened, and wrinkled skin in chronically sun-exposed areas.<br><br>Collagen (option A) provides tensile strength; keratin (option B) is intracellular intermediate filament protein; fibrin (option D) is a clotting protein not contributing to skin elasticity in normal physiological conditions.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A friction blister forms due to separation within',o:['Dermis','Stratum spinosum','Stratum basale','Basement membrane'],a:1,e:`Friction blisters form due to separation within the stratum spinosum; mechanical shearing forces tear desmosomal connections, producing intraepidermal cleavage and fluid accumulation.<br><br>Repeated friction generates heat and mechanical stress that exceed cellular adhesion capacity. The blister roof contains living epidermis. Healing typically occurs within days through reepithelialisation from intact basal layer.<br><br>Dermis (option A) separation produces deeper subepidermal blisters; stratum basale (option C) cleavage occurs in epidermolysis bullosa simplex; basement membrane (option D) cleavage produces subepidermal blisters as in pemphigoid.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Skin color variation is mainly determined by',o:['Collagen density','Number of melanocytes','Keratin thickness','Size and distribution of melanosomes'],a:3,e:`Skin colour variation is mainly determined by size and distribution of melanosomes; darker skin has larger, more dispersed melanosomes packed individually within keratinocytes.<br><br>Lighter skin has smaller melanosomes aggregated in clusters surrounded by membranes. The number of melanocytes per unit area is similar across ethnicities; functional differences in melanosome biology produce visible variation.<br><br>Collagen density (option A) does not affect colour; melanocyte number (option B) is largely constant; keratin thickness (option C) influences pallor in callused skin but does not explain ethnic colour variation across populations.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Arrector pili muscle contraction causes',o:['Goosebumps','Sweating','Vasodilation','Sebum secretion'],a:0,e:`Arrector pili muscle contraction causes goosebumps; sympathetic stimulation triggers smooth muscle contraction, raising the hair follicle and producing the dimpled cutis anserina appearance.<br><br>This vestigial response provided thermal insulation and intimidation in furred ancestors. In humans it is triggered by cold, fear, or strong emotion. The smooth muscle inserts into the papillary dermis at the hair shaft.<br><br>Sweating (option B) involves eccrine glands not arrector pili; vasodilation (option C) involves cutaneous blood vessels; sebum secretion (option D) is from sebaceous glands, none directly produced by arrector pili contraction.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Subcutaneous tissue primarily stores',o:['Protein','Fat','Calcium','Glycogen'],a:1,e:`Subcutaneous tissue primarily stores fat; adipocytes provide energy storage, thermal insulation, mechanical cushioning, and contribute to the contour of body surfaces.<br><br>Adipose tissue is metabolically active, secreting leptin, adiponectin, and inflammatory mediators. Distribution differs between sexes due to hormonal influences. Obesity reflects expanded subcutaneous and visceral adipose mass with metabolic consequences.<br><br>Protein storage (option A) does not occur in adipose tissue; calcium (option C) is stored in bone; glycogen (option D) is stored in liver and muscle, none being the principal subcutaneous storage role.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with vitiligo has destruction of',o:['Fibroblasts','Langerhans cells','Melanocytes','Keratinocytes'],a:2,e:`Vitiligo features destruction of melanocytes; autoimmune attack on melanocytes by cytotoxic CD8 T cells produces depigmented patches with sharp borders, often appearing in symmetric distribution.<br><br>Vitiligo associates with other autoimmune diseases including thyroid disease, type 1 diabetes, and Addison disease. Wood lamp examination accentuates lesions. Treatment includes topical steroids, calcineurin inhibitors, phototherapy, and pigment cell transplantation.<br><br>Fibroblasts (option A) are dermal collagen-producing cells; Langerhans cells (option B) are immune sentinels; keratinocytes (option D) form the epidermis, none being the targeted cell population in vitiligo pathogenesis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Most abundant cell of epidermis',o:['Langerhans cell','Keratinocyte','Merkel cell','Melanocyte'],a:1,e:`Keratinocytes are the most abundant cells of the epidermis, comprising over 95 percent of epidermal cellularity and forming the structural basis of the cutaneous barrier.<br><br>Keratinocytes proliferate from stratum basale, differentiate as they migrate upward, produce keratin filaments, and ultimately form anucleate corneocytes of the stratum corneum that constitute the barrier.<br><br>Langerhans cells (option A) are antigen-presenting cells comprising 2-5 percent; Merkel cells (option C) are mechanoreceptors; melanocytes (option D) provide pigment but represent only 5-10 percent of basal layer cells.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Heat dissipation in skin mainly occurs via',o:['Sebum secretion','Vasoconstriction','Sweating and vasodilation','Keratinization'],a:2,e:`Heat dissipation in skin mainly occurs via sweating and vasodilation; evaporation of eccrine sweat removes heat while dermal vasodilation increases convective and radiative heat loss.<br><br>Hypothalamic preoptic area integrates thermoregulation. Sympathetic cholinergic fibres innervate eccrine glands. Cutaneous vasodilation increases skin blood flow up to 8 L/min during heat stress, dramatically enhancing heat loss.<br><br>Sebum secretion (option A) does not contribute to thermoregulation; vasoconstriction (option B) reduces heat loss in cold; keratinisation (option D) is a continuous structural process unrelated to acute thermoregulatory responses.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Collagen type predominant in dermis',o:['Type IV','Type III only','Type II','Type I'],a:3,e:`Type I collagen predominates in the dermis, comprising over 80 percent of dermal collagen and providing the principal tensile strength of skin throughout adult life.<br><br>Type III collagen contributes about 15 percent and is more abundant in fetal skin and during wound healing. Fibroblasts synthesise procollagen, which undergoes extracellular processing and crosslinking by lysyl oxidase.<br><br>Type IV (option A) is in basement membranes; type III only (option B) understates the dominance of type I; type II (option C) is in cartilage and vitreous, none being the principal dermal collagen.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient develops pressure ulcer due to prolonged ischemia affecting first',o:['Subcutaneous tissue','Bone','Epidermis','Dermis'],a:0,e:`Pressure ulcers develop from prolonged ischaemia first affecting subcutaneous tissue; deep tissue layers receive less perfusion under bony prominences than superficial epidermis.<br><br>Sustained pressure exceeding capillary closing pressure (above 32 mmHg) for 2 hours can initiate damage. Shear forces compound injury. Deep tissue injury may appear initially as a non-blanchable purple area progressing.<br><br>Bone (option B) tolerates ischaemia longer; epidermis (option C) is affected later in stage III/IV ulcers; dermis (option D) is also affected later than subcutaneous fat in pressure-induced ischaemic injury.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Meissner corpuscles detect',o:['Temperature','Fine touch','Vibration deep','Pain'],a:1,e:`Meissner corpuscles detect fine, light, discriminative touch; encapsulated mechanoreceptors in dermal papillae of glabrous skin transmit fast-adapting signals through A-beta fibres.<br><br>These are densely packed in fingertips, lips, and palmar surfaces, mediating two-point discrimination, fine texture detection, and Braille reading. They respond rapidly to skin indentation onset and offset.<br><br>Temperature (option A) is sensed by free nerve endings; vibration deep (option C) is detected by Pacinian corpuscles; pain (option D) is mediated by free nerve endings, not encapsulated touch receptors of the dermal papillae.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The skin barrier lipid matrix mainly contains',o:['Cholesterol, ceramides, fatty acids','Glycogen','Triglycerides only','Phospholipids only'],a:0,e:`Skin barrier lipid matrix mainly contains cholesterol, ceramides, and free fatty acids; these intercellular lipids in the stratum corneum prevent transepidermal water loss.<br><br>Lamellar bodies in stratum granulosum extrude these lipids, which assemble into bilayer sheets between corneocytes. Ceramide deficiency contributes to atopic dermatitis. Topical ceramide-containing emollients restore barrier function.<br><br>Glycogen (option B) is intracellular energy storage; triglycerides only (option C) characterise adipocytes; phospholipids only (option D) form cell membranes but not the unique extracellular lipid lamellae of the stratum corneum.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Nail plate is composed of',o:['Elastin','Collagen','Melanin','Hard keratin'],a:3,e:`Nail plate is composed of hard keratin; tightly packed, heavily disulphide-cross-linked keratin filaments produce the rigid yet flexible structure of the fingernail and toenail.<br><br>Hard keratin contains higher cysteine content than soft keratin of skin. Nail plate grows from the matrix beneath the proximal nail fold at approximately 0.1 mm per day in fingernails.<br><br>Elastin (option A) provides skin elasticity; collagen (option B) is dermal; melanin (option C) is the pigment in skin and hair, none being the structural protein of the nail plate.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Hair growth cycle active phase',o:['Telogen','Resting phase','Anagen','Catagen'],a:2,e:`Anagen is the active growth phase of the hair cycle; matrix keratinocytes proliferate rapidly and the hair shaft elongates over a period of 2-7 years for scalp hair.<br><br>Anagen length determines maximum hair length and varies between body sites. Approximately 85-90 percent of scalp hairs are in anagen at any time. Chemotherapy disrupts anagen, producing diffuse alopecia.<br><br>Telogen (option A) is the resting phase; resting phase (option B) is synonymous with telogen; catagen (option D) is the brief regression phase between anagen and telogen, lasting only 2-3 weeks.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The main function of stratum corneum lipids is',o:['Waterproof barrier','Pigmentation','Sensation','Immune defense'],a:0,e:`Stratum corneum lipids form a waterproof barrier; the lipid lamellae of cholesterol, ceramides, and free fatty acids prevent transepidermal water loss and pathogen entry.<br><br>The brick-and-mortar model describes corneocytes (bricks) embedded in lipid lamellae (mortar). Disruption of this matrix in eczema, ichthyosis, and burns produces dehydration, irritation, and increased infection risk.<br><br>Pigmentation (option B) is from melanin in keratinocytes; sensation (option C) is mediated by nerve endings; immune defence (option D) is largely Langerhans cell function, none being the role of stratum corneum lipids.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with peripheral neuropathy loses temperature sensation mediated by',o:['Merkel cells','Meissner corpuscles','Free nerve endings','Pacinian corpuscles'],a:2,e:`Free nerve endings mediate temperature sensation; specialised endings detect cold and warmth, with TRPM8 and TRPV1 channels respectively transducing thermal stimuli into action potentials.<br><br>Cold thresholds are typically below 35 C while warmth thresholds rise above 35 C. Peripheral neuropathy from diabetes or chemotherapy damages these unmyelinated and thinly myelinated fibres, producing thermal hypoaesthesia.<br><br>Merkel cells (option A) sense pressure and texture; Meissner corpuscles (option B) detect light touch; Pacinian corpuscles (option D) detect vibration and deep pressure, not thermal sensation through TRP channel signalling.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Dermal papillae increase',o:['Sweat production','Surface area for attachment','Sebum secretion','Hair growth only'],a:1,e:`Dermal papillae increase the surface area for attachment between epidermis and dermis; this interdigitation strengthens the dermo-epidermal junction against shearing forces.<br><br>Papillae also accommodate capillary loops supplying epidermal nutrition and Meissner corpuscles for fine touch. They are particularly prominent in glabrous skin of palms and fingertips for mechanical and sensory function.<br><br>Sweat production (option A) is from eccrine glands; sebum secretion (option C) is from sebaceous glands; hair growth only (option D) is at hair follicles, none being the principal function of dermal papillae specifically.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Which layer disappears in blister formation of pemphigus vulgaris?',o:['Dermis','Stratum basale','Stratum corneum','Stratum spinosum'],a:3,e:`Stratum spinosum disappears in pemphigus vulgaris due to acantholysis; autoantibodies against desmoglein-3 disrupt desmosomal adhesion between keratinocytes producing intraepidermal blisters.<br><br>Direct immunofluorescence shows IgG deposition in a fishnet pattern around keratinocytes. Tzanck smear reveals acantholytic cells. Treatment includes systemic corticosteroids and rituximab to deplete autoreactive B cells.<br><br>Dermis (option A) is unaffected; stratum basale (option B) typically remains attached as the floor of the blister; stratum corneum (option C) forms the roof but does not disappear in pemphigus vulgaris pathology.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The major role of keratohyalin granules is',o:['Pigment formation','Sweat secretion','Keratin aggregation','Collagen synthesis'],a:2,e:`Keratohyalin granules aggregate keratin filaments during terminal differentiation; profilaggrin within granules is processed to filaggrin, which crosslinks keratin into dense bundles.<br><br>Filaggrin processing produces natural moisturising factor and amino acid components. Filaggrin gene mutations underlie ichthyosis vulgaris and predispose to atopic dermatitis through impaired barrier function clinically.<br><br>Pigment formation (option A) involves melanocytes and tyrosinase; sweat secretion (option B) is from eccrine glands; collagen synthesis (option D) is from dermal fibroblasts, none being the role of keratohyalin granules.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A person exposed to cold develops vasoconstriction to',o:['Reduce heat loss','Increase heat loss','Increase sweating','Stimulate melanin'],a:0,e:`Cold exposure triggers vasoconstriction to reduce heat loss; sympathetic noradrenergic stimulation contracts cutaneous arterioles, decreasing skin blood flow and conserving core body temperature.<br><br>Cutaneous arteriovenous anastomoses also close in cold, redirecting blood centrally. Severe vasoconstriction may produce frostbite or chilblains. Raynaud phenomenon involves exaggerated cold-induced vasospasm in digital arteries.<br><br>Increase heat loss (option B) is the opposite physiological response; increase sweating (option C) facilitates evaporative cooling in heat; stimulate melanin (option D) occurs with UV exposure, not cold-induced vasomotor adjustment.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Fingerprint patterns arise from',o:['Sebaceous glands','Epidermal ridges','Hair follicles','Dermal fat'],a:1,e:`Fingerprint patterns arise from epidermal ridges; the unique architecture of dermal papillae projecting into overlying epidermis creates the friction ridges visible on palmar and plantar surfaces.<br><br>Ridges form during fetal development and remain unchanged throughout life. They improve grip by increasing friction and amplify tactile sensation through Meissner corpuscles concentrated in the dermal papillae.<br><br>Sebaceous glands (option A) secrete sebum but do not form ridges; hair follicles (option C) are absent from glabrous palmar skin; dermal fat (option D) lies in deeper subcutaneous tissue, not contributing to ridge architecture.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Skin pH normally is',o:['Neutral 7','Variable 10','Alkaline 9','Acidic around 5.5'],a:3,e:`Skin pH is normally acidic, around 5.5; this acid mantle is produced by sebum free fatty acids, sweat lactic acid, and microbial metabolic products on the skin surface.<br><br>Acidic pH inhibits pathogen colonisation and supports beneficial commensal flora. Soaps with alkaline pH disturb the mantle, predisposing to dryness and infection. Newborn skin reaches adult pH within weeks after birth.<br><br>Neutral pH 7 (option A) is intracellular cytoplasmic; alkaline pH 9 (option C) inhibits normal skin function; variable pH 10 (option B) is non-physiological and not the normal cutaneous surface measurement.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Tanning after sun exposure occurs due to increased',o:['Collagen formation','Melanin synthesis','Sebum production','Keratin destruction'],a:1,e:`Tanning after sun exposure occurs due to increased melanin synthesis; UV radiation activates tyrosinase in melanocytes and stimulates melanosome production and transfer to keratinocytes.<br><br>Immediate tanning involves oxidation of preformed melanin within minutes. Delayed tanning develops over days through new melanin synthesis providing sustained photoprotection. Both processes shield epidermal nuclei from further UV damage.<br><br>Collagen formation (option A) is unrelated to tanning; sebum production (option C) is androgen-driven; keratin destruction (option D) does not occur during normal tanning, which is a protective melanocyte response.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The dermis is nourished by',o:['Sebaceous glands','Sweat ducts','Epidermal vessels','Dermal vascular plexus'],a:3,e:`The dermis is nourished by the dermal vascular plexus; the epidermis lacks blood vessels and depends on diffusion from this network for oxygen and nutrient supply.<br><br>Two horizontal plexuses run in superficial and deep dermis, connected by ascending and descending vessels. Cutaneous vasculature also serves thermoregulation through arteriovenous anastomoses regulating blood flow under autonomic control.<br><br>Sebaceous glands (option A) are not vascular sources; sweat ducts (option B) carry secretion not blood; epidermal vessels (option C) do not exist as the epidermis is avascular by definition in normal skin.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Loss of skin elasticity in aging mainly due to degeneration of',o:['Elastin fibers','Glycogen','Melanin','Keratin'],a:0,e:`Loss of skin elasticity in ageing is mainly due to degeneration of elastin fibres; cumulative UV exposure and intrinsic ageing fragment elastic fibres and reduce dermal recoil.<br><br>Solar elastosis describes the accumulation of abnormal elastotic material in chronically photo-exposed skin. Wrinkles, sagging, and reduced tensile strength characterise photoaged dermis with both elastin and collagen changes.<br><br>Glycogen (option B) is not a skin structural component; melanin (option C) provides pigmentation; keratin (option D) is intracellular structural protein, none being responsible for cutaneous elastic recoil in skin.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with anhidrosis most likely has dysfunction of',o:['Sebaceous glands','Hair follicles','Eccrine glands','Apocrine glands'],a:2,e:`Anhidrosis most likely indicates dysfunction of eccrine glands; absence of sweat production from these widespread thermoregulatory glands impairs heat dissipation through evaporation in affected patients.<br><br>Eccrine glands are innervated by sympathetic cholinergic fibres. Anhidrotic ectodermal dysplasia is a genetic cause; autonomic neuropathy and anticholinergic medications are acquired causes producing reduced or absent sweat output.<br><br>Sebaceous glands (option A) do not produce sweat; hair follicles (option B) are unrelated to sweating; apocrine glands (option D) localise to axillae and groin, not contributing significantly to thermoregulatory sweat output.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'The reticular dermis mainly contains',o:['Dense collagen bundles','Smooth muscle','Loose connective tissue','Adipose tissue only'],a:0,e:`Reticular dermis mainly contains dense collagen bundles; thick interwoven type I collagen fibres provide tensile strength and resistance to mechanical stress in the deeper dermal layer.<br><br>Elastic fibres are also present but in lower density. Reticular dermis lies beneath papillary dermis and above subcutaneous tissue. Sweat glands, hair follicles, and Pacinian corpuscles reside within this layer.<br><br>Smooth muscle (option B) is found in arrector pili; loose connective tissue (option C) characterises papillary dermis; adipose tissue only (option D) characterises subcutaneous tissue, not the principal reticular dermal composition.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Skin acts as immune organ mainly due to presence of',o:['Myocytes','Adipocytes','Fibroblasts','Langerhans cells'],a:3,e:`Skin acts as an immune organ mainly due to the presence of Langerhans cells; these dendritic antigen-presenting cells link cutaneous innate immunity with systemic adaptive responses.<br><br>Langerhans cells contain Birbeck granules and capture antigens for transport to lymph nodes. Skin-resident T cells, dermal dendritic cells, and keratinocyte-derived cytokines complete the cutaneous immune surveillance network in healthy skin.<br><br>Myocytes (option A) are muscle cells; adipocytes (option B) store fat; fibroblasts (option C) produce extracellular matrix, none of which serve professional antigen-presenting functions in cutaneous immune responses.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Cyanosis becomes visible when deoxygenated hemoglobin exceeds',o:['3 g/dL','8 g/dL','5 g/dL','1 g/dL'],a:2,e:`Cyanosis becomes clinically visible when deoxygenated haemoglobin in capillaries exceeds approximately 5 g/dL; below this concentration, the bluish discolouration is not detectable on examination.<br><br>Cyanosis may be central (involving lips, tongue, mucous membranes) reflecting arterial hypoxaemia, or peripheral (acral) reflecting reduced peripheral perfusion. Anaemic patients may not manifest cyanosis despite severe hypoxia clinically.<br><br>3 g/dL (option A) is below the visibility threshold; 8 g/dL (option B) is well above; 1 g/dL (option D) is undetectable, leaving 5 g/dL as the established threshold for clinical cyanosis recognition.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'The main function of subcutaneous fat is',o:['Sensory perception','Insulation and energy storage','Immune response','Pigmentation'],a:1,e:`Subcutaneous fat primarily provides insulation and energy storage; lipid reserves serve as long-term metabolic fuel while the layer reduces conductive heat loss to the environment.<br><br>Subcutaneous tissue also cushions underlying structures from mechanical impact and contributes to body contour. Adipocytes secrete leptin, adiponectin, and inflammatory cytokines, making the layer endocrine and metabolically active.<br><br>Sensory perception (option A) is from dermal receptors; immune response (option C) is from Langerhans cells and lymphocytes; pigmentation (option D) is from melanocytes, none being principal subcutaneous fat functions.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The skin is derived embryologically from',o:['Endoderm only','Mesoderm only','Ectoderm and mesoderm','Neural crest only'],a:2,e:`Skin is derived embryologically from ectoderm and mesoderm; surface ectoderm forms the epidermis and appendages while mesoderm contributes the dermis and subcutaneous tissue components.<br><br>Neural crest cells, also of ectodermal origin, contribute melanocytes, sensory nerves, and Schwann cells. Reciprocal signalling between ectoderm and mesoderm during development determines regional skin specialisation across the body.<br><br>Endoderm only (option A) forms internal linings; mesoderm only (option B) ignores the ectodermal epidermis; neural crest only (option D) is an incomplete origin since most skin components arise from ectoderm-mesoderm interaction.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The dermo-epidermal junction primarily functions to',o:['Anchor epidermis to dermis','Produce pigment','Store fat','Secrete sweat'],a:0,e:`The dermo-epidermal junction primarily anchors the epidermis to the dermis; hemidesmosomes, lamina lucida, lamina densa, and anchoring fibrils together provide mechanical attachment and barrier function.<br><br>Disorders of this junction produce blistering diseases. Bullous pemphigoid targets BP180/BP230 in hemidesmosomes; epidermolysis bullosa subtypes affect different junction components with corresponding levels of skin cleavage clinically.<br><br>Producing pigment (option B) is melanocyte function; storing fat (option C) is subcutaneous tissue role; secreting sweat (option D) is from eccrine glands, none being the structural anchoring function of the junction.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Melanin is synthesized from tyrosine by the enzyme',o:['Elastase','Tyrosinase','Lipase','Collagenase'],a:1,e:`Melanin is synthesised from tyrosine by the enzyme tyrosinase; this copper-containing enzyme catalyses hydroxylation of tyrosine to dopa and subsequent oxidation to dopaquinone in melanosomes.<br><br>Tyrosinase deficiency causes oculocutaneous albinism. Eumelanin (brown-black) and pheomelanin (red-yellow) derive from common dopaquinone precursor. Melanocyte-stimulating hormone increases tyrosinase activity, contributing to pigmentation responses.<br><br>Elastase (option A) degrades elastin; lipase (option C) hydrolyses lipids; collagenase (option D) breaks down collagen, none of which catalyse melanin synthesis from tyrosine in melanosomes physiologically.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The acid mantle of the skin mainly protects against',o:['UV radiation','Mechanical trauma','Heat loss','Bacterial colonization'],a:3,e:`The acid mantle of skin mainly protects against bacterial colonisation; the acidic pH around 5.5 inhibits growth of pathogenic bacteria while supporting beneficial commensal flora.<br><br>The acid mantle is produced by sebum free fatty acids, sweat lactic acid, and microbial metabolic products. Alkaline soaps disturb the mantle, predisposing to dryness, irritation, and bacterial overgrowth on skin.<br><br>UV radiation (option A) is blocked by melanin and stratum corneum; mechanical trauma (option B) is resisted by collagen; heat loss (option C) is regulated by sweating and vasomotor responses, not pH itself.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'In thick skin, the additional epidermal layer present is',o:['Stratum germinativum','Stratum reticulare','Stratum lucidum','Stratum papillare'],a:2,e:`Thick skin contains the additional layer stratum lucidum; this clear, translucent layer between stratum granulosum and stratum corneum is found only in palms and soles where mechanical protection is needed.<br><br>Stratum lucidum cells are anucleate with eleidin, a transformation product of keratohyalin. Thick skin lacks hair follicles and sebaceous glands but has abundant eccrine sweat glands and Meissner corpuscles for sensation.<br><br>Stratum germinativum (option A) is another name for stratum basale; stratum reticulare (option B) is reticular dermis; stratum papillare (option D) is papillary dermis, none being unique to thick skin.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Epidermal turnover time in normal adult skin is approximately',o:['60 days','14 days','7 days','28 days'],a:3,e:`Epidermal turnover time in normal adult skin is approximately 28 days; basal keratinocytes proliferate, differentiate during upward migration, and shed as corneocytes from the stratum corneum surface.<br><br>Turnover accelerates in psoriasis (3-7 days), producing the characteristic silvery scales of immature differentiation. Slowing of turnover with ageing contributes to dry, rough skin texture in elderly patients clinically.<br><br>60 days (option A) is too long for normal turnover; 14 days (option B) is too short; 7 days (option C) is the psoriatic turnover not normal, leaving 28 days as the standard adult value.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The primary barrier to percutaneous drug absorption lies in',o:['Hair follicle','Stratum corneum','Dermis','Subcutaneous tissue'],a:1,e:`The primary barrier to percutaneous drug absorption lies in the stratum corneum; the lipid lamellae and corneocyte arrangement form the rate-limiting layer for transdermal drug delivery.<br><br>Drug penetration depends on molecular size, lipid solubility, and concentration gradient. Hydrophobic drugs cross more readily. Stratum corneum hydration, occlusion, and chemical penetration enhancers improve transdermal delivery in pharmaceutical formulations.<br><br>Hair follicle (option A) provides a minor adnexal route; dermis (option C) is well perfused once drug crosses the barrier; subcutaneous tissue (option D) is reached only after dermal absorption, not the rate-limiting step.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Keratin intermediate filaments are mainly composed of',o:['Cytokeratins','Actin','Myosin','Tubulin'],a:0,e:`Keratin intermediate filaments are mainly composed of cytokeratins; over 50 different cytokeratin genes encode pairs of acidic and basic keratins expressed in different epithelial subtypes specifically.<br><br>Basal keratinocytes express K5 and K14; suprabasal cells express K1 and K10. Mutations in these keratins underlie epidermolysis bullosa simplex and bullous congenital ichthyosiform erythroderma respectively, producing skin fragility.<br><br>Actin (option B) is microfilament protein; myosin (option C) is muscle motor protein; tubulin (option D) forms microtubules, none being intermediate filament keratin proteins of the epidermis specifically.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Melanosomes are transferred to keratinocytes through',o:['Gap junctions','Osmosis','Active phagocytosis of dendrite tips','Diffusion'],a:2,e:`Melanosomes are transferred to keratinocytes through active phagocytosis of melanocyte dendrite tips; this contact-dependent process delivers pigment to surrounding cells in coordinated fashion.<br><br>Each melanocyte serves approximately 36 keratinocytes through dendritic processes. Transferred melanosomes accumulate over keratinocyte nuclei as supranuclear caps, shielding nuclear DNA from UV-induced damage in basal cells.<br><br>Gap junctions (option A) allow ionic exchange not melanosome transfer; osmosis (option B) moves water; diffusion (option D) does not transfer membrane-bound organelles, leaving phagocytosis as the established transfer mechanism.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The main chromophore responsible for UV-induced tanning is',o:['Melanin','Bilirubin','Hemoglobin','Keratin'],a:0,e:`Melanin is the main chromophore responsible for UV-induced tanning; both immediate oxidation of preformed melanin and delayed synthesis of new melanin contribute to the tanning response.<br><br>Melanin absorbs UVA and UVB radiation, dissipating energy as heat. Eumelanin is more photoprotective than pheomelanin. Tanning provides moderate protection equivalent to SPF 2-4 only, insufficient for prolonged sun exposure.<br><br>Bilirubin (option B) accumulates in jaundice without UV interaction; haemoglobin (option C) gives skin pinkness through circulation; keratin (option D) is structural and does not absorb UV significantly compared with melanin.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Apocrine glands become active primarily during',o:['Old age','Puberty','Childhood','Birth'],a:1,e:`Apocrine glands become active primarily during puberty under hormonal influence; androgens trigger functional maturation of these glands in axillae, groin, and areolae regions.<br><br>Apocrine secretion is initially odourless; bacterial metabolism produces volatile compounds responsible for body odour. Stress and emotional stimuli increase apocrine output, while heat and exercise primarily activate eccrine glands.<br><br>Old age (option A) features declining apocrine activity; childhood (option C) precedes apocrine maturation; birth (option D) shows immature glands, leaving puberty as the period of full functional activation hormonally.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The nail matrix is responsible for',o:['Nail color','Nail hydration','Nail sensation','Nail growth'],a:3,e:`The nail matrix is responsible for nail growth; mitotically active matrix keratinocytes proliferate and differentiate to produce the hard keratin of the nail plate continuously.<br><br>The matrix lies beneath the proximal nail fold and extends as the lunula visible at the base. Matrix damage from trauma or inflammation produces nail dystrophies, ridging, and growth disturbances clinically.<br><br>Nail colour (option A) reflects underlying nail bed vasculature; nail hydration (option B) depends on water absorption from environment; nail sensation (option C) involves nail bed sensory innervation, not matrix function.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Acanthosis refers to',o:['Epidermal hyperplasia of stratum spinosum','Dermal edema','Loss of keratin','Epidermal thinning'],a:0,e:`Acanthosis refers to epidermal hyperplasia of the stratum spinosum; thickening of the spinous layer produces the characteristic histological appearance seen in psoriasis and chronic dermatoses.<br><br>Acanthosis often accompanies hyperkeratosis and parakeratosis in inflammatory conditions. Acanthosis nigricans presents clinically as velvety hyperpigmented plaques in skin folds, associated with insulin resistance and visceral malignancy.<br><br>Dermal oedema (option B) is spongiosis-related and dermal; loss of keratin (option C) is hypokeratosis; epidermal thinning (option D) is atrophy, all distinct from the hyperplastic acanthosis pattern histologically.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The primary function of sebum is to',o:['Regulate temperature','Lubricate skin and hair','Provide sensation','Produce vitamin D'],a:1,e:`The primary function of sebum is to lubricate skin and hair; sebaceous glands secrete a lipid mixture of triglycerides, wax esters, squalene, and cholesterol onto the skin surface.<br><br>Sebum maintains skin and hair pliability, contributes to the acid mantle, and provides mild antimicrobial action through free fatty acids. Excess production combined with follicular hyperkeratinisation underlies acne pathogenesis.<br><br>Temperature regulation (option A) is via sweat and vasomotor responses; sensation (option C) is via dermal receptors; vitamin D production (option D) requires UVB and 7-dehydrocholesterol, not sebum directly.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The papillary dermis contains predominantly',o:['Thick collagen bundles','Adipocytes','Loose connective tissue','Cartilage'],a:2,e:`The papillary dermis predominantly contains loose connective tissue; thin collagen fibres, elastic fibres, ground substance, and capillary loops support epidermal nutrition and tactile sensation.<br><br>The papillary dermis interdigitates with the epidermis through dermal papillae, increasing surface area for nutrient exchange. Meissner corpuscles and Merkel cell complexes provide tactile sensation in this layer.<br><br>Thick collagen bundles (option A) characterise reticular dermis; adipocytes (option B) are subcutaneous; cartilage (option D) is not present in skin, all distinct from the loose connective tissue of papillary dermis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Hair growth is cyclical; the resting phase is called',o:['Exogen','Catagen','Anagen','Telogen'],a:3,e:`The resting phase of the hair growth cycle is called telogen; matrix activity ceases and the club hair remains in the follicle for approximately 2-3 months before shedding.<br><br>Approximately 10-15 percent of scalp hairs are in telogen at any time. Telogen effluvium describes accelerated entry into telogen following stressors such as childbirth, severe illness, or major surgery.<br><br>Exogen (option A) refers specifically to hair shedding; catagen (option B) is the brief regression phase; anagen (option C) is the active growth phase, not the resting phase being asked about here.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Vitamin D synthesis requires conversion of 7-dehydrocholesterol in',o:['Epidermis','Subcutaneous tissue','Sweat glands','Dermis'],a:0,e:`Vitamin D synthesis begins with conversion of 7-dehydrocholesterol in the epidermis; UVB radiation cleaves the B ring producing previtamin D3, which thermally isomerises to vitamin D3 (cholecalciferol).<br><br>Subsequent hydroxylations occur in liver (25-position) and kidney (1-alpha-position) to produce active calcitriol. Sunscreen, dark skin, and northern latitudes reduce cutaneous vitamin D synthesis substantially throughout life.<br><br>Subcutaneous tissue (option B) contains adipose not 7-dehydrocholesterol; sweat glands (option C) and dermis (option D) are not the conversion sites, leaving the epidermis as the principal cutaneous synthesis location.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The primary immune cell of epidermis presenting antigen to T-cells is',o:['Fibroblast','Langerhans cell','Keratinocyte','Melanocyte'],a:1,e:`The principal immune cell of the epidermis presenting antigen to T cells is the Langerhans cell; these dendritic cells are derived from bone marrow and reside between keratinocytes.<br><br>Langerhans cells contain tennis-racket-shaped Birbeck granules visible on electron microscopy. They capture antigens, migrate to regional lymph nodes, and present to T lymphocytes, central to contact dermatitis pathogenesis.<br><br>Fibroblast (option A) is dermal collagen-producer; keratinocyte (option C) is the structural epidermal cell; melanocyte (option D) produces pigment, none of which serve as professional antigen-presenting cells in the epidermis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The tactile receptor associated with fine touch in fingertips is',o:['Free nerve ending','Pacinian corpuscle','Ruffini ending','Meissner corpuscle'],a:3,e:`Meissner corpuscles in fingertips detect fine touch; encapsulated mechanoreceptors in dermal papillae of glabrous skin transmit fast-adapting signals through A-beta fibres for tactile discrimination.<br><br>These receptors are densely packed in fingertips, lips, and palmar surfaces, mediating two-point discrimination, fine texture detection, and Braille reading. They respond rapidly to skin indentation onset and offset.<br><br>Free nerve ending (option A) detects pain and temperature; Pacinian corpuscle (option B) detects vibration and deep pressure; Ruffini ending (option C) detects skin stretch, none being the primary fine touch receptor.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The dermis receives nutrition from',o:['Sweat ducts','Sebaceous glands','Dermal vascular plexus','Epidermal diffusion'],a:2,e:`The dermis receives nutrition from the dermal vascular plexus; superficial and deep horizontal plexuses interconnect via ascending and descending vessels supplying all dermal structures with blood.<br><br>Cutaneous vasculature also serves thermoregulation through arteriovenous anastomoses regulating blood flow under autonomic control. The epidermis is avascular and depends entirely on diffusion from the underlying dermal capillary network.<br><br>Sweat ducts (option A) carry secretion not blood; sebaceous glands (option B) are nutrient consumers not suppliers; epidermal diffusion (option D) cannot supply the deeper dermis, leaving the dermal plexus as the source.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A wheal in urticaria is produced due to',o:['Epidermal necrosis','Keratin deposition','Subcutaneous fibrosis','Dermal edema'],a:3,e:`A wheal in urticaria is produced due to dermal oedema; histamine and other mediators released from mast cells increase vascular permeability, allowing fluid to accumulate in the dermis.<br><br>Wheals are transient, raised, erythematous, intensely pruritic lesions resolving within 24 hours without scarring. Acute urticaria often follows allergen exposure; chronic urticaria persisting beyond 6 weeks frequently has autoimmune basis.<br><br>Epidermal necrosis (option A) characterises toxic epidermal necrolysis; keratin deposition (option B) is hyperkeratosis; subcutaneous fibrosis (option C) is panniculitis sequela, none being the wheal mechanism.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The major component of the extracellular matrix giving tensile strength is',o:['Collagen type I','Keratin','Elastin','Collagen type II'],a:0,e:`The major component of extracellular matrix giving tensile strength is collagen type I; this fibrillar collagen forms thick bundles in the reticular dermis resisting mechanical loading.<br><br>Type I collagen accounts for over 80 percent of dermal collagen with type III contributing the remainder. Fibroblasts synthesise procollagen which undergoes extracellular processing and lysyl oxidase crosslinking to mature collagen.<br><br>Keratin (option B) is intracellular intermediate filament protein; elastin (option C) provides elastic recoil not tensile strength; collagen type II (option D) is in cartilage and vitreous, not the principal dermal collagen.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Transepidermal water loss mainly occurs through',o:['Hair follicles only','Sebaceous ducts','Stratum corneum diffusion','Sweat glands'],a:2,e:`Transepidermal water loss mainly occurs through stratum corneum diffusion; water diffuses passively across the lipid lamellae of the cornified layer at a low baseline rate in healthy skin.<br><br>Disruption of the stratum corneum lipid matrix in eczema, ichthyosis, and burns increases transepidermal water loss substantially. Measurement of transepidermal water loss provides an objective index of barrier function.<br><br>Hair follicles only (option A) contribute minimally; sebaceous ducts (option B) carry sebum not water; sweat glands (option D) produce active sweat secretion, distinct from the passive diffusional water loss being asked about.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The basement membrane contains collagen type',o:['V','IV','I','II'],a:1,e:`The basement membrane contains collagen type IV; this non-fibrillar collagen forms a planar network in the lamina densa providing structural integrity to the dermo-epidermal junction.<br><br>Type IV collagen interacts with laminin, nidogen, and perlecan to form basement membrane. Anti-glomerular basement membrane antibodies in Goodpasture syndrome target type IV collagen, causing pulmonary haemorrhage and glomerulonephritis.<br><br>Type V (option A) is in fibrillar collagens of dermis and other tissues; type I (option C) is principal dermal fibrillar collagen; type II (option D) is cartilage, none being the basement membrane network collagen.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The skin microbiome mainly resides in',o:['Stratum corneum and appendages','Dermis','Subcutaneous fat','Blood vessels'],a:0,e:`The skin microbiome mainly resides in the stratum corneum and skin appendages; commensal bacteria, fungi, and viruses inhabit the surface, hair follicles, and sweat duct openings densely.<br><br>Staphylococcus epidermidis, Cutibacterium acnes, Malassezia species, and others form the resident flora. Microbiome dysbiosis contributes to acne, atopic dermatitis, and other conditions. Antibiotics disturb composition allowing overgrowth.<br><br>Dermis (option B) is normally sterile; subcutaneous fat (option C) lacks resident flora; blood vessels (option D) in healthy skin are sterile, leaving stratum corneum and appendages as the microbial habitat.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'UVB radiation primarily causes',o:['Dermal fibrosis','Sweat suppression','DNA pyrimidine dimers','Immediate tanning'],a:2,e:`UVB radiation primarily causes DNA pyrimidine dimers; UVB photons (290-320 nm) are absorbed by adjacent pyrimidine bases, forming cyclobutane pyrimidine dimers and 6-4 photoproducts in DNA.<br><br>These mutagenic lesions are repaired by nucleotide excision repair. Defective repair in xeroderma pigmentosum causes high skin cancer risk. UVB also causes sunburn and stimulates melanin synthesis providing photoprotection.<br><br>Dermal fibrosis (option A) is not a UVB effect; sweat suppression (option B) is unrelated; immediate tanning (option D) is UVA-mediated through preformed melanin oxidation, not the UVB DNA damage mechanism.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Sebaceous glands are absent in',o:['Face','Scalp','Chest','Palms and soles'],a:3,e:`Sebaceous glands are absent from palms and soles; these glabrous skin sites lack hair follicles and their associated sebaceous glands, contrasting with hair-bearing skin elsewhere on the body.<br><br>Palms and soles compensate with thicker stratum corneum, abundant eccrine sweat glands, and Meissner corpuscles. The absence of sebum on these surfaces allows them to maintain grip without lubrication interference.<br><br>Face (option A) has highest sebaceous gland density; scalp (option B) has dense sebaceous glands; chest (option C) also contains sebaceous glands, leaving palms and soles uniquely lacking sebaceous gland presence anatomically.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The primary mediator of pruritus released from mast cells is',o:['Acetylcholine','Histamine','Dopamine','Serotonin'],a:1,e:`The primary mediator of pruritus released from mast cells is histamine; binding of histamine to H1 receptors on sensory C fibres triggers itch transmission to the spinal cord centrally.<br><br>Other pruritogens include serotonin, neuropeptides, and proteases. Antihistamines target H1 receptors and provide variable relief depending on cause. Chronic pruritus often involves non-histaminergic pathways requiring different therapeutic approaches.<br><br>Acetylcholine (option A) mediates muscle contraction and parasympathetic effects; dopamine (option C) is a CNS neurotransmitter; serotonin (option D) plays a minor role compared to the dominant histamine mechanism in mast cell-mediated itch.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The arrector pili muscle is innervated by',o:['Sympathetic fibers','Somatic motor fibers','Parasympathetic fibers','Sensory fibers'],a:0,e:`The arrector pili muscle is innervated by sympathetic fibres; postganglionic noradrenergic stimulation triggers smooth muscle contraction, raising hair follicles and producing piloerection (goosebumps) on skin.<br><br>Sympathetic activation occurs with cold exposure, fear, or strong emotion. The vestigial response provided thermal insulation and intimidation in furred ancestors. Persistent piloerection occurs in autonomic dysreflexia neurological emergencies.<br><br>Somatic motor fibres (option B) innervate skeletal muscle; parasympathetic fibres (option C) do not innervate arrector pili; sensory fibres (option D) carry afferent information, not motor commands to smooth muscle in the dermis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The reticular dermis mainly consists of',o:['Muscle','Loose connective tissue','Cartilage','Dense irregular connective tissue'],a:3,e:`Reticular dermis mainly consists of dense irregular connective tissue; thick interwoven type I collagen bundles oriented in multiple directions provide tensile strength and resistance to mechanical stress.<br><br>Elastic fibres are also present at lower density. Sweat glands, hair follicles, and Pacinian corpuscles reside within reticular dermis. The layer extends from beneath papillary dermis to the subcutaneous interface below.<br><br>Muscle (option A) is found only as arrector pili and dartos; loose connective tissue (option B) characterises papillary dermis; cartilage (option C) is absent from skin entirely, leaving dense irregular tissue as correct.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A vesicle is defined as a fluid-filled lesion less than',o:['2 cm','1 cm','0.5 cm','5 cm'],a:2,e:`A vesicle is a fluid-filled lesion smaller than 0.5 cm; larger fluid-filled lesions are termed bullae, distinguishing the two by size on clinical morphological description of skin lesions.<br><br>Vesicles arise from intraepidermal or subepidermal cleavage. Causes include herpes simplex virus, varicella-zoster, contact dermatitis, and friction. Group of vesicles on erythematous base suggests viral aetiology classically clinically.<br><br>2 cm (option A) and 5 cm (option D) describe larger lesions termed bullae or larger collections; 1 cm (option B) is the threshold for bullae rather than vesicles, leaving 0.5 cm as the upper vesicle limit.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The main source of skin regeneration after superficial injury is',o:['Vascular endothelium','Hair follicle stem cells','Subcutaneous adipocytes','Dermal fibroblasts'],a:1,e:`The main source of skin regeneration after superficial injury is hair follicle stem cells; bulge stem cells in the upper outer root sheath provide progenitor cells for epidermal repair locally.<br><br>Interfollicular epidermal stem cells in basal layer also contribute. Burns destroying follicles leave only marginal epidermis for regeneration, slowing healing substantially. Sweat gland stem cells additionally contribute to wound coverage.<br><br>Vascular endothelium (option A) regenerates blood vessels; subcutaneous adipocytes (option C) regenerate fat; dermal fibroblasts (option D) produce collagen for scar formation, none being the principal source of epidermal regeneration.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Merkel cells are associated with',o:['Vibration','Temperature','Pressure sensation','Pain'],a:2,e:`Merkel cells are associated with pressure sensation; these slowly adapting type I mechanoreceptors lie in the basal epidermis adjacent to terminal nerve endings of sensory afferents.<br><br>Merkel cell-neurite complexes detect sustained pressure and texture, providing high spatial resolution. They concentrate in fingertips, lips, and external genitalia. Merkel cell carcinoma is an aggressive cutaneous neuroendocrine malignancy.<br><br>Vibration (option A) is detected by Pacinian corpuscles; temperature (option B) is sensed by free nerve endings; pain (option D) is also free-nerve-ending mediated, distinct from Merkel cell pressure and texture sensation.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'UVA radiation penetrates primarily into',o:['Epidermis only','Dermis','Subcutaneous fat','Stratum corneum'],a:1,e:`UVA radiation penetrates primarily into the dermis; longer wavelengths (320-400 nm) reach deeper than UVB and contribute to photoageing and dermal connective tissue damage over time.<br><br>UVA produces reactive oxygen species damaging collagen and elastin, manifesting as solar elastosis and wrinkles. Window glass blocks UVB but transmits UVA. Sunscreens with broad-spectrum coverage block both wavelengths effectively.<br><br>Epidermis only (option A) is reached more by UVB; subcutaneous fat (option C) is too deep for UV penetration; stratum corneum (option D) is the most superficial layer, all distinct from the dermal UVA penetration depth.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Skin blanching on pressure occurs due to',o:['Pigment loss','Vasodilation','Keratin destruction','Blood displacement from vessels'],a:3,e:`Skin blanching on pressure occurs due to blood displacement from vessels; mechanical compression of dermal capillaries empties them temporarily, producing local pallor that resolves on release.<br><br>The capillary refill test exploits this phenomenon to assess perfusion. Refill within 2 seconds is normal; prolonged refill suggests hypoperfusion or shock. Non-blanching purpura indicates extravasated blood not displaceable by pressure.<br><br>Pigment loss (option A) is depigmentation as in vitiligo; vasodilation (option B) increases blood flow not displaces it; keratin destruction (option C) does not produce transient blanching, none matching the mechanism.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The most common cell in dermis is',o:['Fibroblast','Melanocyte','Mast cell','Keratinocyte'],a:0,e:`The most common cell in the dermis is the fibroblast; these spindle-shaped cells synthesise collagen, elastin, and ground substance maintaining the extracellular matrix throughout life.<br><br>Fibroblasts also play roles in wound healing, immune signalling, and tissue remodelling. They proliferate during repair and differentiate into myofibroblasts contracting wound edges. Excessive fibroblast activity produces keloid and hypertrophic scarring.<br><br>Melanocyte (option B) is epidermal; mast cell (option C) is present but less abundant; keratinocyte (option D) is the principal epidermal cell, none being the most numerous dermal cell type compared to fibroblasts.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Desmosomes connect',o:['Nerves to vessels','Dermis to muscle','Epidermis to dermis','Keratinocyte to keratinocyte'],a:3,e:`Desmosomes connect keratinocyte to keratinocyte; these specialised intercellular junctions link cytokeratin filaments across cell boundaries through cadherin proteins desmoglein and desmocollin.<br><br>Pemphigus vulgaris autoantibodies target desmoglein-3, breaking desmosomal adhesion in stratum spinosum and producing flaccid intraepidermal blisters with positive Nikolsky sign on examination.<br><br>Nerves to vessels (option A) is not a desmosomal function; dermis to muscle (option B) involves connective tissue attachments; epidermis to dermis (option C) is hemidesmosomal not desmosomal, leaving keratinocyte-keratinocyte as correct.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Hemidesmosomes connect',o:['Dermis to fat','Keratinocytes to basement membrane','Nerves to epidermis','Sweat gland to duct'],a:1,e:`Hemidesmosomes connect keratinocytes to the basement membrane; these specialised junctions link basal keratinocyte cytokeratin filaments to the underlying lamina densa via integrin and laminin interactions.<br><br>Bullous pemphigoid autoantibodies target hemidesmosome proteins BP180 and BP230, producing tense subepidermal blisters. Junctional epidermolysis bullosa results from genetic defects in laminin-332 within the basement membrane.<br><br>Dermis to fat (option A) involves connective tissue attachments; nerves to epidermis (option C) involves free nerve endings; sweat gland to duct (option D) is glandular continuity, none being the hemidesmosomal connection.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The normal skin flora helps by',o:['Competing with pathogens','Producing toxins','Destroying collagen','Increasing pH'],a:0,e:`The normal skin flora helps by competing with pathogens for nutrients and adhesion sites; commensal bacteria produce antimicrobial peptides and free fatty acids inhibiting pathogen growth on skin.<br><br>Staphylococcus epidermidis, Cutibacterium acnes, and Corynebacterium species form the resident flora. Antibiotic disruption allows overgrowth of Staphylococcus aureus, Candida, and other pathogens, predisposing to infection clinically.<br><br>Producing toxins (option B) is the role of pathogenic organisms; destroying collagen (option C) characterises tissue infection; increasing pH (option D) would harm the protective acid mantle, not benefit normal skin.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The subcutaneous layer mainly acts as',o:['Sensory organ','Pigment reservoir','Insulation and energy storage','Immune organ'],a:2,e:`The subcutaneous layer mainly acts as insulation and energy storage; adipose tissue provides thermal protection and long-term metabolic fuel reserves regulated by neuroendocrine signals.<br><br>Subcutaneous tissue also cushions underlying structures from mechanical impact and contributes to body contour. Adipocytes secrete leptin, adiponectin, and inflammatory cytokines, making the layer endocrine and metabolically active.<br><br>Sensory organ (option A) is the role of dermal receptors; pigment reservoir (option B) is fulfilled by epidermal melanocytes; immune organ (option D) is largely Langerhans cell function, distinct from subcutaneous fat roles.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Immediate tanning after sun exposure is due to',o:['Oxidation of existing melanin','Collagen deposition','New melanin synthesis','Keratin thickening'],a:0,e:`Immediate tanning after sun exposure is due to oxidation of existing melanin; UVA radiation oxidises preformed melanin within minutes, producing transient darkening before delayed melanogenesis begins.<br><br>Immediate pigment darkening fades within hours unless followed by delayed tanning from new melanin synthesis. Delayed tanning develops over 2-3 days through tyrosinase induction and provides longer-lasting photoprotection clinically.<br><br>Collagen deposition (option B) is unrelated to tanning; new melanin synthesis (option C) occurs in delayed tanning not immediate; keratin thickening (option D) is a separate adaptive response not contributing to immediate pigment darkening.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A bulla is defined as lesion larger than',o:['0.5 cm','1 cm','5 cm','2 cm'],a:1,e:`A bulla is defined as a fluid-filled lesion larger than 1 cm; smaller fluid-filled lesions are termed vesicles, distinguishing the two by size on clinical morphological description.<br><br>Bullae arise from intraepidermal or subepidermal cleavage. Causes include bullous pemphigoid, pemphigus vulgaris, bullous impetigo, and severe contact dermatitis. Tense versus flaccid bullae indicate level of cleavage histologically.<br><br>0.5 cm (option A) defines vesicle threshold; 5 cm (option C) describes much larger collections; 2 cm (option D) is above bulla threshold but not the defining size, leaving 1 cm as the conventional cut-off.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The most superficial dermal vascular network is',o:['Muscular plexus','Deep plexus','Subcutaneous plexus','Superficial horizontal plexus'],a:3,e:`The most superficial dermal vascular network is the superficial horizontal plexus; this network at the papillary-reticular dermis junction supplies the epidermis through ascending capillary loops.<br><br>A deeper horizontal plexus lies at the dermal-subcutaneous junction. Vertical anastomoses connect the two networks. Cutaneous vasculature serves both nutrition and thermoregulation through arteriovenous anastomoses regulated by autonomic control.<br><br>Muscular plexus (option A) is not a standard cutaneous network; deep plexus (option B) is the deeper of the two; subcutaneous plexus (option C) describes vasculature below dermis, none being the most superficial dermal network.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Sweat secretion is mediated by neurotransmitter',o:['Norepinephrine','Dopamine','Acetylcholine','GABA'],a:2,e:`Sweat secretion is mediated by acetylcholine; sympathetic cholinergic postganglionic fibres activate muscarinic receptors on eccrine gland clear cells, stimulating watery sweat production.<br><br>This is unusual since most sympathetic fibres release noradrenaline. Anticholinergic medications reduce sweating and may cause hyperthermia. Botulinum toxin injection blocks acetylcholine release, treating axillary or palmar hyperhidrosis effectively.<br><br>Norepinephrine (option A) mediates most other sympathetic effects; dopamine (option B) is a CNS neurotransmitter; GABA (option D) is inhibitory in the CNS, none being the eccrine gland neurotransmitter.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The primary cell forming scar tissue is',o:['Keratinocyte','Fibroblast','Melanocyte','Mast cell'],a:1,e:`The primary cell forming scar tissue is the fibroblast; these spindle-shaped cells synthesise collagen during wound repair, contracting wound edges as myofibroblasts in the proliferative phase.<br><br>Fibroblasts deposit type III collagen initially, gradually replaced by type I collagen during remodelling over months. Excessive fibroblast activity produces hypertrophic scars and keloids extending beyond original wound boundaries.<br><br>Keratinocyte (option A) reepithelialises wounds but does not form scar tissue; melanocyte (option C) repigments healed skin; mast cell (option D) modulates inflammation, none being the principal scar-forming cell.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A macule is defined as',o:['Pus filled lesion','Nodular lesion','Fluid filled lesion','Flat lesion without elevation'],a:3,e:`A macule is a flat lesion without elevation; macules are circumscribed areas of colour change less than 1 cm in diameter, distinguished from papules and patches by lack of palpable elevation.<br><br>Examples include freckles, café-au-lait spots, and early viral exanthems. A patch is a larger flat lesion exceeding 1 cm. Recognition of basic primary lesion morphology is fundamental to dermatological diagnosis clinically.<br><br>Pus-filled lesion (option A) is a pustule; nodular lesion (option B) is palpable and elevated; fluid-filled lesion (option C) is a vesicle or bulla, all distinct from the flat non-elevated character defining macule lesions.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The skin acts as endocrine organ mainly through',o:['Vitamin D synthesis','Cortisol secretion','Thyroxine release','Insulin production'],a:0,e:`Skin acts as an endocrine organ mainly through vitamin D synthesis; UVB-driven conversion of 7-dehydrocholesterol in the epidermis initiates the vitamin D pathway with downstream calcium homeostasis effects.<br><br>Subsequent hydroxylation in liver and kidney produces active calcitriol regulating intestinal calcium absorption and bone mineralisation. Sebocytes and other skin cells also produce neuropeptides and hormones in autocrine and paracrine fashion.<br><br>Cortisol secretion (option B) occurs in adrenal cortex; thyroxine release (option C) is from thyroid; insulin production (option D) is from pancreatic beta cells, none being principal endocrine functions of the skin.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Keloid formation results from excessive',o:['Melanin production','Keratinization','Collagen deposition','Elastin synthesis'],a:2,e:`Keloid formation results from excessive collagen deposition; fibroblasts overproduce type I and type III collagen during wound healing, extending fibrous tissue beyond original wound boundaries.<br><br>Keloids preferentially affect darker skin and characteristic sites including earlobes, sternum, and shoulders. They differ from hypertrophic scars which remain within wound borders. Treatment includes intralesional steroids, surgery, and laser.<br><br>Melanin production (option A) is unrelated to keloids; keratinisation (option B) is epidermal; elastin synthesis (option D) is dermal but not the principal mechanism, leaving collagen overdeposition as the keloid mechanism.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The primary barrier against UV radiation is',o:['Sebum','Melanin','Sweat','Collagen'],a:1,e:`The primary barrier against UV radiation is melanin; this pigment absorbs UVB and UVA wavelengths, dissipating energy as heat and shielding nuclear DNA from photodamage in keratinocytes.<br><br>Melanosomes accumulate over keratinocyte nuclei as supranuclear caps. Eumelanin (brown-black) is more photoprotective than pheomelanin (red-yellow). Melanin protection is moderate, equivalent to SPF 2-4 only, in unsupplemented natural skin.<br><br>Sebum (option A) is lipid lubrication; sweat (option C) is thermoregulatory; collagen (option D) provides tensile strength, none being the principal photoprotective absorber compared to the dedicated melanin pigment system.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Skin temperature regulation occurs mainly via',o:['Sebum secretion','Hair growth','Sweating and vasomotor changes','Keratin turnover'],a:2,e:`Skin temperature regulation occurs mainly via sweating and vasomotor changes; eccrine sweat evaporation removes heat while cutaneous vasodilation or vasoconstriction adjusts radiative and convective heat exchange.<br><br>Hypothalamic preoptic area integrates thermoregulation. Sympathetic cholinergic fibres innervate eccrine glands; sympathetic adrenergic fibres control vasomotor tone. Cutaneous blood flow can range from minimal to over 8 L/min during stress.<br><br>Sebum secretion (option A) does not contribute to thermoregulation; hair growth (option B) is too slow for active regulation; keratin turnover (option D) is structural, distinct from active thermoregulatory mechanisms in human skin.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The most common site of scabies involvement in adults is',o:['Face','Scalp','Back','Interdigital web spaces'],a:3,e:`Interdigital web spaces are the most common scabies sites in adults; thin skin and warmth favour mite burrowing in finger and toe webs producing intensely pruritic linear lesions.<br><br>Other classic sites include flexor wrists, axillae, periumbilical area, genitalia, and breasts. Female mites burrow into the stratum corneum, lay eggs, and trigger delayed hypersensitivity producing nocturnal itch.<br><br>Face (option A) and scalp (option B) are usually spared in adults except in immunocompromised crusted scabies; back (option C) involvement is less common, leaving interdigital webs as the predominant adult site.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'The causative organism of scabies is',o:['Sarcoptes scabiei var hominis','Pediculus humanus','Dermatophyte','Demodex folliculorum'],a:0,e:`Sarcoptes scabiei var hominis is the causative organism of scabies; this obligate human ectoparasite mite burrows into the stratum corneum producing intensely pruritic infestation.<br><br>Female mites lay 2-3 eggs daily over 1-2 months. Transmission occurs through prolonged skin-to-skin contact, fomites in crusted scabies. Diagnosis is by skin scraping showing mites, eggs, or faecal pellets microscopically.<br><br>Pediculus humanus (option B) is the louse of pediculosis; dermatophytes (option C) cause tinea infections; Demodex folliculorum (option D) inhabits hair follicles causing rosacea, distinct from the scabies mite organism.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Nocturnal itching is characteristic feature of',o:['Melasma','Psoriasis','Scabies','Vitiligo'],a:2,e:`Nocturnal itching is the characteristic feature of scabies; pruritus worsens at night when warmth and inactivity activate mite movement and host hypersensitivity responses to mite antigens.<br><br>Itching may persist for weeks after successful treatment due to retained mite antigens. Multiple household members typically affected supports diagnosis. Excoriations and secondary bacterial infection complicate untreated infestation clinically.<br><br>Melasma (option A) is hyperpigmentation without itch; psoriasis (option B) has variable pruritus not nocturnal pattern; vitiligo (option D) is depigmentation without itching, none matching the nocturnal pruritus of scabies.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'First line treatment of scabies',o:['Permethrin 5% cream','Clindamycin','Oral acyclovir','Ketoconazole cream'],a:0,e:`Permethrin 5% cream is first-line treatment for scabies; this synthetic pyrethroid kills mites by disrupting sodium channel function in the parasite nervous system effectively.<br><br>Apply from neck down, leave 8-14 hours, then wash off. Repeat in one week. Treat all household and close contacts simultaneously even if asymptomatic. Wash bedding and clothing in hot water.<br><br>Clindamycin (option B) treats bacterial infection; oral acyclovir (option C) treats herpes; ketoconazole cream (option D) treats fungal infection, none being effective scabicidal therapy in human skin infestation.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Norwegian scabies is associated with',o:['Diabetes insipidus','Iron deficiency','Hyperthyroidism','Immunocompromised state'],a:3,e:`Norwegian (crusted) scabies is associated with immunocompromised state; reduced cell-mediated immunity allows uncontrolled mite proliferation producing thick hyperkeratotic crusts containing thousands of mites.<br><br>Common in HIV/AIDS, organ transplant recipients, and elderly debilitated patients. Highly contagious through fomites and casual contact. Treatment requires combined topical permethrin and oral ivermectin, often with keratolytic agents.<br><br>Diabetes insipidus (option A) is unrelated; iron deficiency (option B) is general anaemia; hyperthyroidism (option C) is metabolic, none being the principal predisposing condition for crusted scabies development.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Pediculosis capitis commonly affects',o:['Neonates','School children','Elderly men','Athletes'],a:1,e:`Pediculosis capitis commonly affects school children; head-to-head contact during play and sharing of combs or hats facilitates transmission of head lice in primary school populations.<br><br>Female lice attach eggs (nits) to hair shafts close to scalp. Itching results from saliva-induced hypersensitivity. Diagnosis by visualisation of live lice or nits within 1 cm of scalp on close inspection.<br><br>Neonates (option A) are unusual hosts; elderly men (option C) and athletes (option D) are not typical risk groups, leaving school children as the principal demographic for head lice transmission and infestation.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Nits in pediculosis are found attached to',o:['Nails','Skin','Sebaceous gland','Hair shaft'],a:3,e:`Nits in pediculosis are found attached to the hair shaft; female lice cement eggs to hair fibres close to the scalp using waterproof adhesive resistant to most treatments.<br><br>Nits within 1 cm of scalp suggest active infestation; those further out indicate older deposition. Wet combing with fine-toothed nit comb removes eggs after pediculicide treatment for complete eradication.<br><br>Nails (option A) and skin (option B) are not nit attachment sites; sebaceous glands (option C) are gland structures not visible attachment points, leaving the hair shaft as the unique nit attachment location.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Drug of choice for pediculosis capitis',o:['Salicylic acid','Acyclovir','Permethrin lotion','Steroids'],a:2,e:`Permethrin lotion is the drug of choice for pediculosis capitis; this synthetic pyrethroid kills lice by disrupting sodium channel function in the parasite nervous system effectively.<br><br>Apply to dry hair, leave 10 minutes, then rinse. Repeat in 7-10 days to kill newly hatched lice. Resistance to permethrin is increasing; alternatives include malathion, spinosad, or oral ivermectin.<br><br>Salicylic acid (option A) is keratolytic for hyperkeratosis; acyclovir (option B) treats herpes; steroids (option D) treat inflammation, none being effective pediculicidal agents in head lice infestation.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Impetigo is most commonly caused by',o:['Mycobacterium leprae','Staphylococcus aureus','Herpes simplex virus','Candida albicans'],a:1,e:`Impetigo is most commonly caused by Staphylococcus aureus; this Gram-positive coccus produces characteristic honey-coloured crusts in superficial epidermal infection of children.<br><br>Streptococcus pyogenes is the second leading cause and may produce post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis. Bullous impetigo specifically caused by exfoliative toxin-producing S. aureus strains. Treatment includes topical mupirocin or oral antibiotics.<br><br>Mycobacterium leprae (option A) causes leprosy; herpes simplex virus (option C) causes vesicular eruptions; Candida albicans (option D) causes thrush and intertrigo, none being the typical impetigo organism.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Honey colored crusted lesions are typical of',o:['Impetigo','Psoriasis','Tinea corporis','Urticaria'],a:0,e:`Honey-coloured crusted lesions are typical of impetigo; the characteristic golden-yellow crust forms over erosions following rupture of initial vesicles in this superficial bacterial infection.<br><br>Lesions commonly affect face, especially around mouth and nose. Highly contagious through direct contact. Bullous impetigo presents with flaccid bullae from exfoliative toxin. Treatment includes topical mupirocin or oral antibiotics.<br><br>Psoriasis (option B) shows silvery scale; tinea corporis (option C) shows annular lesion with central clearing; urticaria (option D) shows wheals without crust, all distinct from the honey-coloured impetigo crusts.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Erysipelas commonly involves',o:['Muscle','Upper dermis','Subcutaneous tissue only','Epidermis only'],a:1,e:`Erysipelas commonly involves the upper dermis; this superficial bacterial infection presents with sharply demarcated, raised, erythematous, tender plaques with prominent lymphatic involvement on skin.<br><br>Streptococcus pyogenes is the principal causative organism. Common sites include face and lower legs. Fever and lymphadenopathy accompany cutaneous findings. Treatment with penicillin or amoxicillin produces rapid clinical response.<br><br>Muscle (option A) is involved in necrotising fasciitis or pyomyositis; subcutaneous tissue only (option C) characterises cellulitis; epidermis only (option D) characterises impetigo, not the upper dermal erysipelas pathology.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Cellulitis most commonly caused by',o:['Streptococcus pyogenes','Mycobacterium','Candida','HSV'],a:0,e:`Cellulitis is most commonly caused by Streptococcus pyogenes; this Gram-positive coccus produces deep dermal and subcutaneous infection with diffuse erythema, warmth, and tenderness without sharp borders.<br><br>Staphylococcus aureus is the second leading cause. Risk factors include lymphoedema, venous insufficiency, and skin breaks. Treatment with flucloxacillin or amoxicillin-clavulanate covers both organisms in empirical therapy.<br><br>Mycobacterium (option B) causes leprosy and tuberculosis; Candida (option C) causes thrush and intertrigo; HSV (option D) causes vesicular eruption, none being the typical cellulitis pathogen in immunocompetent patients.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Furuncle is infection of',o:['Nerve ending','Sebaceous cyst','Hair follicle','Sweat gland'],a:2,e:`A furuncle is an infection of the hair follicle; deep folliculitis with surrounding tissue involvement produces the characteristic painful red nodule with central necrosis and pus formation.<br><br>Staphylococcus aureus is the typical organism. Risk factors include diabetes, obesity, and immunosuppression. Treatment includes warm compresses, incision and drainage if fluctuant, and antibiotics for systemic features or facial lesions.<br><br>Nerve ending (option A) is not infected by furuncles; sebaceous cyst (option B) is a separate entity; sweat gland (option D) infection is hidradenitis suppurativa, none being the hair follicle-based furuncle pathology.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Carbuncle is best described as',o:['Viral infection','Fungal plaque','Parasitic lesion','Multiple interconnected furuncles'],a:3,e:`A carbuncle is best described as multiple interconnected furuncles; deep extension and coalescence of follicular abscesses produce the characteristic large, painful, erythematous mass with multiple drainage points.<br><br>Staphylococcus aureus is the typical organism. Carbuncles commonly occur on neck, back, and thighs. Treatment includes incision and drainage plus systemic antibiotics. Diabetes and immunosuppression predispose to recurrent and severe disease.<br><br>Viral infection (option A) is not the carbuncle aetiology; fungal plaque (option B) describes dermatophytosis; parasitic lesion (option C) characterises infestations, none being the bacterial multi-furuncle pathology of carbuncles.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Hansen disease caused by',o:['Mycobacterium tuberculosis','Nocardia','Mycobacterium leprae','Treponema pallidum'],a:2,e:`Hansen disease is caused by Mycobacterium leprae; this acid-fast bacillus produces chronic granulomatous infection with predilection for skin and peripheral nerves with characteristic clinical features.<br><br>Spectrum ranges from tuberculoid (strong cell-mediated immunity, few bacilli) to lepromatous (weak immunity, many bacilli). Diagnosis by skin biopsy and slit skin smear for AFB. Treatment with multidrug therapy (rifampicin, dapsone, clofazimine).<br><br>Mycobacterium tuberculosis (option A) causes pulmonary tuberculosis; Nocardia (option B) causes nocardiosis; Treponema pallidum (option D) causes syphilis, none being the leprosy organism specifically.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Lepromatous leprosy characterized by',o:['Weak cell mediated immunity','Strong cell mediated immunity','No bacteria','Pure nerve disease'],a:0,e:`Lepromatous leprosy is characterised by weak cell-mediated immunity; this allows extensive bacterial multiplication producing widespread skin lesions with abundant acid-fast bacilli on smear.<br><br>Patients have multiple symmetric lesions with infiltrated skin, leonine facies, madarosis (loss of eyebrows), and saddle-nose deformity. Slit skin smear positivity is high. Treatment requires extended multidrug therapy regimens.<br><br>Strong cell mediated immunity (option B) characterises tuberculoid leprosy; no bacteria (option C) is incorrect since lepromatous shows abundant bacilli; pure nerve disease (option D) is primary neuritic leprosy, distinct entity.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Tinea corporis caused by',o:['Virus','Bacteria','Parasite','Dermatophytes'],a:3,e:`Tinea corporis is caused by dermatophytes; Trichophyton, Microsporum, and Epidermophyton species invade keratinised tissue producing the characteristic annular erythematous plaque with central clearing.<br><br>Diagnosis is by KOH preparation showing branching hyphae or fungal culture. Treatment includes topical azoles or terbinafine for limited disease and oral antifungals for extensive or refractory infection clinically.<br><br>Virus (option A) causes warts and herpes; bacteria (option B) cause impetigo and cellulitis; parasite (option C) causes scabies and pediculosis, none being the dermatophyte tinea corporis aetiology specifically.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Central clearing with active border lesion suggests',o:['Urticaria','Tinea infection','Psoriasis','Eczema'],a:1,e:`Central clearing with active border lesion suggests tinea infection; the dermatophyte spreads centrifugally with leading edge inflammation and central resolution producing the classic annular ringworm appearance.<br><br>KOH preparation of scrapings from the active border shows branching hyphae. Treatment with topical azoles or terbinafine for limited disease and oral antifungals for extensive infection produces good response in most cases.<br><br>Urticaria (option A) shows wheals without scale; psoriasis (option C) shows silvery scaling plaques without central clearing; eczema (option D) is poorly demarcated and pruritic without the annular pattern of tinea.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'KOH mount used to diagnose',o:['Fungal infection','Parasitic infection','Viral infection','Bacterial infection'],a:0,e:`KOH mount is used to diagnose fungal infection; potassium hydroxide dissolves keratin in skin scrapings revealing branching septate hyphae of dermatophytes or pseudohyphae and budding yeasts of Candida.<br><br>Specimens are taken from active lesion borders. Culture on Sabouraud agar identifies specific fungal species. Wood lamp examination may show fluorescence with certain dermatophytes (Microsporum) but not Trichophyton.<br><br>Parasitic (option B) infection is diagnosed by direct visualisation of mites or eggs; viral (option C) by Tzanck smear or PCR; bacterial (option D) by Gram stain or culture, none using KOH mount diagnostically.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Oral antifungal drug for extensive dermatophyte infection',o:['Penicillin','Acyclovir','Ivermectin','Fluconazole'],a:3,e:`Fluconazole is an oral antifungal for extensive dermatophyte infection; this triazole inhibits fungal lanosterol 14-alpha-demethylase producing ergosterol depletion and fungal cell membrane disruption.<br><br>Terbinafine is a more potent alternative for dermatophytes through squalene epoxidase inhibition. Itraconazole is also effective. Treatment duration varies from weeks for skin to months for nail dermatophytosis (onychomycosis).<br><br>Penicillin (option A) treats bacterial infection; acyclovir (option B) treats herpes; ivermectin (option C) treats parasitic infestations, none being effective oral antifungal therapy for dermatophyte infection.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Pityriasis versicolor caused by',o:['Aspergillus','Microsporum','Malassezia furfur','Candida albicans'],a:2,e:`Pityriasis versicolor is caused by Malassezia furfur; this lipophilic yeast is part of normal skin flora that proliferates and produces hypo- or hyperpigmented patches in seborrhoeic areas.<br><br>KOH preparation shows the characteristic spaghetti-and-meatballs appearance of hyphae and yeast forms. Treatment includes topical selenium sulfide, ketoconazole shampoo, or oral azoles for extensive disease cases.<br><br>Aspergillus (option A) causes opportunistic infection of immunocompromised patients; Microsporum (option B) is a dermatophyte causing tinea; Candida albicans (option D) causes thrush, none being the pityriasis versicolor organism.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Hypopigmented macules on chest with fine scaling seen in',o:['Vitiligo','Tinea versicolor','Psoriasis','Leprosy'],a:1,e:`Hypopigmented macules on chest with fine scaling are seen in tinea versicolor; Malassezia furfur disrupts melanocyte function producing the characteristic hypo- or hyperpigmented patches with fine scale.<br><br>Lesions concentrate on chest, back, shoulders, and upper arms in seborrhoeic distribution. KOH preparation confirms diagnosis. Recurrence is common; prophylactic topical treatment may reduce frequency in susceptible patients clinically.<br><br>Vitiligo (option A) is fully depigmented without scale; psoriasis (option C) shows thick silvery scale; leprosy (option D) features anaesthetic patches with thickened nerves, all distinct from tinea versicolor pattern.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Herpes simplex virus typically causes',o:['Ulcers only','Plaques','Nodules','Vesicular lesions'],a:3,e:`Herpes simplex virus typically causes vesicular lesions; grouped vesicles on an erythematous base evolving to crusted erosions are characteristic of orolabial or genital HSV infection.<br><br>Tzanck smear shows multinucleated giant cells. Direct fluorescent antibody and PCR are more sensitive diagnostic tests. Treatment with oral acyclovir, valacyclovir, or famciclovir reduces severity and duration of outbreaks effectively.<br><br>Ulcers only (option A) describes chancroid; plaques (option B) characterise psoriasis; nodules (option C) suggest tumours, none being the typical vesicular cluster pattern of HSV infection clinically.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Treatment of herpes simplex infection',o:['Ketoconazole','Acyclovir','Ivermectin','Amoxicillin'],a:1,e:`Acyclovir is the treatment of herpes simplex infection; this guanosine analogue is phosphorylated by viral thymidine kinase and inhibits viral DNA polymerase, blocking viral replication selectively.<br><br>Oral acyclovir is used for orolabial and genital HSV. Intravenous therapy treats severe disease including HSV encephalitis. Valacyclovir has improved bioavailability. Suppressive therapy reduces recurrent outbreak frequency in selected patients.<br><br>Ketoconazole (option A) is an antifungal; ivermectin (option C) is antiparasitic; amoxicillin (option D) is antibacterial, none being effective antiviral therapy for herpes simplex virus infection in humans.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Varicella zoster virus reactivation causes',o:['Rubella','Measles','Shingles','Chickenpox'],a:2,e:`Varicella zoster virus reactivation causes shingles; latent virus in dorsal root ganglia reactivates with declining cell-mediated immunity producing painful dermatomal vesicular eruption.<br><br>Postherpetic neuralgia is the most common complication, particularly in elderly patients. Antiviral therapy within 72 hours reduces severity. Vaccination (Shingrix) effectively prevents shingles and postherpetic neuralgia in older adults.<br><br>Rubella (option A) is German measles caused by rubivirus; measles (option B) is morbillivirus; chickenpox (option D) is primary varicella infection, distinct from reactivation shingles being asked about.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Dermatomal painful vesicles indicate',o:['Herpes zoster','Tinea corporis','Scabies','Impetigo'],a:0,e:`Dermatomal painful vesicles indicate herpes zoster; reactivation of latent varicella zoster virus from dorsal root ganglia produces unilateral vesicular eruption respecting dermatomal boundaries.<br><br>Pain may precede rash by days. Common dermatomes include thoracic, ophthalmic (V1), and lumbar. Antiviral therapy within 72 hours reduces severity and postherpetic neuralgia incidence. Disseminated zoster suggests immunocompromise.<br><br>Tinea corporis (option B) is annular fungal infection; scabies (option C) shows web-space burrows; impetigo (option D) features honey-crusted bacterial lesions, none matching the dermatomal vesicular pattern of zoster.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Molluscum contagiosum lesions are',o:['Plaques','Vesicles','Pustules','Umbilicated papules'],a:3,e:`Molluscum contagiosum lesions are umbilicated papules; this poxvirus infection produces 2-5 mm pearly flesh-coloured papules with central depression containing infectious viral material.<br><br>Transmission occurs through skin-to-skin contact and fomites. Common in children and sexually active adults. Lesions self-resolve over months to years. Treatment includes cryotherapy, curettage, or topical agents for cosmetic concerns.<br><br>Plaques (option A) are flat-topped lesions; vesicles (option B) are fluid-filled; pustules (option C) contain purulent material, none being the characteristic umbilicated papule of molluscum contagiosum.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Warts are caused by',o:['HPV','CMV','HSV','EBV'],a:0,e:`Warts are caused by HPV; human papillomavirus infects keratinocytes producing benign hyperkeratotic papules with characteristic punctate haemorrhagic dots from thrombosed capillaries on surface.<br><br>Different HPV types cause common, plantar, flat, and genital warts. Transmission through direct contact with skin or fomites. Treatment includes salicylic acid, cryotherapy, imiquimod, and surgical removal for resistant lesions.<br><br>CMV (option B) causes cytomegalovirus infection; HSV (option C) causes herpes; EBV (option D) causes mononucleosis and lymphoma, none being the wart aetiology specifically in human skin infections.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Condyloma acuminata caused by',o:['HIV','HSV','HPV','HBV'],a:2,e:`Condyloma acuminata are caused by HPV; human papillomavirus types 6 and 11 produce benign verrucous papules and cauliflower-like masses on anogenital skin.<br><br>HPV-16 and HPV-18 are oncogenic types associated with cervical, anal, and oropharyngeal cancers. HPV vaccination prevents infection with the major oncogenic and wart-causing strains in adolescents and young adults.<br><br>HIV (option A) causes immunodeficiency syndrome; HSV (option B) causes herpes; HBV (option D) causes hepatitis B, none being the condyloma acuminata aetiology in anogenital warts clinically.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Treatment of common wart',o:['Steroid cream','Salicylic acid','Antibiotics','Antihistamines'],a:1,e:`Salicylic acid is the treatment of common wart; this keratolytic agent dissolves stratum corneum, gradually removing infected tissue while triggering immune response against viral antigens.<br><br>Daily application after paring usually clears warts within weeks to months. Combination with cryotherapy improves response rates. Imiquimod and intralesional bleomycin are alternatives for resistant warts in refractory cases.<br><br>Steroid cream (option A) is anti-inflammatory not antiviral; antibiotics (option C) treat bacterial infection; antihistamines (option D) treat allergic conditions, none being effective wart treatment in human cutaneous HPV infection.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Secondary bacterial infection of scabies commonly due to',o:['HSV','Mycobacterium','Candida','Staphylococcus aureus'],a:3,e:`Secondary bacterial infection of scabies is commonly due to Staphylococcus aureus; excoriations from intense pruritus break the skin barrier allowing bacterial colonisation and impetigo formation.<br><br>Streptococcus pyogenes also causes secondary infection and may produce post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis. Treatment combines scabicide for the mite with topical or oral antibiotics for bacterial superinfection of excoriated lesions.<br><br>HSV (option A) is herpetic; Mycobacterium (option B) causes tuberculosis and leprosy; Candida (option C) is fungal, none being the typical bacterial superinfection pathogen of scabies excoriations clinically.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Ivermectin oral is useful in',o:['Crusted scabies','Vitiligo','Melasma','Psoriasis'],a:0,e:`Oral ivermectin is useful in crusted scabies; this antiparasitic drug binds glutamate-gated chloride channels in the mite, paralysing and killing the organism throughout the body.<br><br>Crusted (Norwegian) scabies requires combined topical permethrin and oral ivermectin due to thick hyperkeratotic crusts harbouring thousands of mites. Two doses one week apart improve eradication rates substantially.<br><br>Vitiligo (option B) is autoimmune depigmentation; melasma (option C) is hyperpigmentation; psoriasis (option D) is inflammatory hyperproliferation, none being conditions requiring ivermectin therapy in dermatology.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Leprosy nerve commonly involved earliest',o:['Facial nerve','Ulnar nerve','Median nerve','Sciatic nerve'],a:1,e:`The ulnar nerve is commonly involved earliest in leprosy; superficial location and proximity to skin make the nerve susceptible to Mycobacterium leprae infection at the elbow particularly.<br><br>Other commonly affected nerves include median, common peroneal, posterior tibial, and great auricular. Nerve thickening, sensory loss, and motor weakness develop progressively. Slit skin smear and biopsy confirm diagnosis.<br><br>Facial nerve (option A) involvement is less common; median nerve (option C) and sciatic nerve (option D) are also less typical, leaving the ulnar nerve as the principal early peripheral nerve in leprosy.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Acid fast bacilli seen in slit skin smear indicates',o:['HSV','Tinea','Leprosy','Scabies'],a:2,e:`Acid-fast bacilli on slit skin smear indicate leprosy; Mycobacterium leprae appears as red rod-shaped organisms after Ziehl-Neelsen staining of slit-incision dermal smears from suspected lesions.<br><br>Bacterial index quantifies organism load. Lepromatous leprosy shows abundant bacilli; tuberculoid form shows few or none. Skin biopsy with Fite stain provides additional diagnostic confirmation in difficult cases clinically.<br><br>HSV (option A) is diagnosed by Tzanck or PCR; tinea (option B) by KOH; scabies (option D) by skin scraping for mites, none using slit skin smear acid-fast staining diagnostically.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Satellite lesions around erythematous plaque typical of',o:['Psoriasis','Candida infection','Impetigo','Tinea'],a:1,e:`Satellite lesions around erythematous plaques are typical of Candida infection; the central plaque with surrounding small pustules and papules is characteristic of cutaneous candidiasis in moist areas.<br><br>Candida albicans thrives in warm moist intertriginous areas including groin, axillae, and inframammary folds. KOH preparation shows pseudohyphae and budding yeasts. Treatment includes topical azoles or nystatin antifungal preparations.<br><br>Psoriasis (option A) shows well-demarcated plaques without satellite lesions; impetigo (option C) features honey-coloured crusts; tinea (option D) shows central clearing without satellites, distinct patterns clinically.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Oral thrush caused by',o:['Bacteria','HSV','Dermatophyte','Candida albicans'],a:3,e:`Oral thrush is caused by Candida albicans; this opportunistic yeast produces white pseudomembranous plaques on oral mucosa that scrape off revealing erythematous mucosa beneath.<br><br>Risk factors include immunosuppression, diabetes, broad-spectrum antibiotic use, inhaled corticosteroids, and infancy. Treatment with oral nystatin suspension or topical clotrimazole is typically effective. Refractory cases may need fluconazole.<br><br>Bacteria (option A) cause bacterial pharyngitis or stomatitis; HSV (option B) causes herpetic gingivostomatitis; dermatophyte (option C) does not infect oral mucosa, none being the oral thrush aetiology specifically.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Kaposi varicelliform eruption occurs in',o:['Vitiligo','Tinea versicolor','Atopic dermatitis with HSV','Psoriasis'],a:2,e:`Kaposi varicelliform eruption occurs in atopic dermatitis with HSV; widespread herpes simplex virus infection of damaged eczematous skin produces the severe disseminated vesicular eruption known as eczema herpeticum.<br><br>Patients present with monomorphic punched-out vesicles, fever, and lymphadenopathy. Risk of viraemia and end-organ involvement makes this a medical emergency. Urgent intravenous acyclovir is required for systemic disease.<br><br>Vitiligo (option A) does not predispose to herpetic infection; tinea versicolor (option B) is fungal; psoriasis (option D) is rarely complicated by Kaposi varicelliform, all distinct from atopic eczema-HSV interaction.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Most contagious stage of varicella',o:['Vesicular stage','Crust stage','Scar stage','Before rash'],a:0,e:`The vesicular stage is the most contagious stage of varicella; chickenpox virus is shed from active vesicles before crusting completes seroconversion and infection.<br><br>Patients are infectious from 1-2 days before rash until all lesions are crusted, typically 5-7 days. Airborne and contact precautions are required. Vaccination provides effective primary prevention in childhood populations widely.<br><br>Crust stage (option B) reflects healing with reduced shedding; scar stage (option C) is post-resolution; before rash (option D) shows minimal contagion compared to active vesicles, leaving vesicular stage as most contagious.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Treatment of cellulitis includes',o:['Antivirals','Antiparasitic','Systemic antibiotics','Antifungals'],a:2,e:`Treatment of cellulitis includes systemic antibiotics; deep dermal and subcutaneous bacterial infection requires oral or intravenous antibacterial agents covering Streptococcus pyogenes and Staphylococcus aureus.<br><br>Flucloxacillin or amoxicillin-clavulanate are first-line oral options. Severe disease, immunocompromise, or sepsis warrant intravenous therapy. Marking the border helps assess treatment response over 48-72 hours of empirical treatment.<br><br>Antivirals (option A) treat viral infections; antiparasitic (option B) treats infestations; antifungals (option D) treat fungal disease, none being effective for bacterial cellulitis caused by Gram-positive organisms.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Folliculitis most commonly caused by',o:['Staphylococcus aureus','Virus','Candida','Mite'],a:0,e:`Folliculitis is most commonly caused by Staphylococcus aureus; this Gram-positive coccus infects hair follicles producing painful pustules surrounding the follicular opening.<br><br>Pseudomonas aeruginosa causes hot tub folliculitis from contaminated water sources. Pityrosporum folliculitis from Malassezia presents as itchy follicular papules. Treatment depends on causative organism and disease extent clinically.<br><br>Virus (option B) causes herpetic folliculitis rarely; Candida (option C) is fungal cause; mite (option D) describes Demodex folliculitis, none being the most common bacterial folliculitis pathogen in humans.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Boil formation is due to infection of',o:['Epidermis only','Hair follicle and surrounding tissue','Sweat ducts','Dermal vessels'],a:1,e:`Boil formation is due to infection of hair follicle and surrounding tissue; deep folliculitis with extension into perifollicular dermis produces the painful red nodule with central pustulation.<br><br>Staphylococcus aureus is the typical organism. Risk factors include diabetes, obesity, and immunosuppression. Treatment includes warm compresses, incision and drainage if fluctuant, and antibiotics for systemic features or facial location.<br><br>Epidermis only (option A) describes superficial impetigo; sweat ducts (option C) is hidradenitis; dermal vessels (option D) describes vasculitis, none being the deep follicular pathology of furuncles or boils.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Dermatophytes invade primarily',o:['Muscle','Nerves','Blood vessels','Keratinized tissue'],a:3,e:`Dermatophytes invade primarily keratinised tissue; these fungi possess keratinases enabling them to digest and live on the keratin of skin, hair, and nails specifically.<br><br>Three genera: Trichophyton, Microsporum, and Epidermophyton. Different species prefer different keratin substrates and body sites. Diagnosis by KOH and culture; treatment with topical or oral azoles and terbinafine.<br><br>Muscle (option A), nerves (option B), and blood vessels (option C) lack keratin and do not support dermatophyte growth, leaving keratinised epidermis, hair, and nail as the unique substrates for these fungi.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Scabies burrow best seen in',o:['Thigh','Finger web spaces','Back','Face'],a:1,e:`Scabies burrows are best seen in finger web spaces; the thin glabrous skin between fingers permits visualisation of the linear or serpentine grey burrow tracks left by the female mite.<br><br>Other classic burrow sites include flexor wrists, periumbilical area, and genitalia. Burrow scraping yields mites, eggs, or faecal pellets visible under microscopy. Burrow ink test enhances visualisation in clinical practice.<br><br>Thigh (option A), back (option C), and face (option D) are unusual burrow sites in adult scabies, leaving finger web spaces as the most reliable site for clinical and microscopic identification.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Tzanck smear useful in diagnosing',o:['Bacterial infection','Parasitic infection','Herpes virus infections','Fungal infection'],a:2,e:`Tzanck smear is useful in diagnosing herpes virus infections; scrapings from the base of vesicles show multinucleated giant cells with molded nuclei characteristic of herpetic cytopathic effect.<br><br>The test cannot distinguish HSV from VZV. Direct fluorescent antibody and PCR are more sensitive and specific. Tzanck remains useful as rapid bedside test for suspected herpes simplex or varicella zoster.<br><br>Bacterial infection (option A) is diagnosed by Gram stain or culture; parasitic (option B) by direct mite or egg visualisation; fungal (option D) by KOH preparation, none using the Tzanck technique diagnostically.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Rose gardener’s disease refers to',o:['Sporotrichosis','Tinea','Scabies','Impetigo'],a:0,e:`Rose gardener's disease refers to sporotrichosis; Sporothrix schenckii enters through skin trauma from rose thorns producing nodular lymphocutaneous lesions ascending along lymphatic channels.<br><br>Initial papulopustular lesion at inoculation site followed by chain of nodules along proximal lymphatics. Diagnosis by culture or histology showing yeast forms. Treatment with itraconazole for several months produces resolution.<br><br>Tinea (option B) is dermatophyte infection; scabies (option C) is mite infestation; impetigo (option D) is bacterial superficial infection, none being the rose gardener's lymphocutaneous fungal infection specifically.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Black dots in tinea capitis represent',o:['Pus','Keratin debris','Blood','Broken hair shafts'],a:3,e:`Black dots in tinea capitis represent broken hair shafts; ectothrix or endothrix fungal invasion weakens the shaft producing breakage at the scalp surface leaving residual stubs.<br><br>Trichophyton tonsurans is the main cause of black dot tinea capitis in many regions. Diagnosis by KOH and culture from scrapings or plucked hairs. Treatment with oral griseofulvin or terbinafine produces resolution.<br><br>Pus (option A) suggests kerion; keratin debris (option B) describes scaling; blood (option C) appears in trauma or vasculitis, none being the broken hair shafts of black dot tinea capitis specifically.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Pseudohyphae on microscopy indicate',o:['Staphylococcus','Candida','HSV','Mycobacterium'],a:1,e:`Pseudohyphae on microscopy indicate Candida; this opportunistic yeast forms elongated cells joined end to end with constrictions at septations distinguishing them from true septate hyphae.<br><br>KOH preparation reveals budding yeasts and pseudohyphae in cutaneous and mucosal candidiasis. Candida albicans is the most common species but other species including C. glabrata are increasingly identified causing various disorders.<br><br>Staphylococcus (option A) shows Gram-positive cocci in clusters; HSV (option C) is diagnosed by Tzanck smear; Mycobacterium (option D) requires acid-fast staining, none showing pseudohyphae on routine microscopy.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Post streptococcal glomerulonephritis complication of',o:['Herpes','Tinea','Impetigo','Scabies'],a:2,e:`Post-streptococcal glomerulonephritis is a complication of impetigo; specific nephritogenic strains of Streptococcus pyogenes following skin infection trigger immune complex glomerular injury 1-2 weeks later.<br><br>Patients develop haematuria, hypertension, and oedema with low complement levels and elevated streptococcal antibodies. Most children recover spontaneously; treatment of streptococcal infection does not prevent post-infectious glomerulonephritis once exposure occurs.<br><br>Herpes (option A) does not cause post-streptococcal sequelae; tinea (option B) and scabies (option D) are not streptococcal, none being the cutaneous source of post-streptococcal renal disease specifically.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Erythema nodosum associated with',o:['Tuberculosis','Candida','Scabies','HSV'],a:0,e:`Erythema nodosum is associated with tuberculosis; this panniculitis presents as tender erythematous nodules on shins reflecting immune response to underlying systemic disease.<br><br>Other causes include streptococcal infection, sarcoidosis, inflammatory bowel disease, drugs (sulfonamides, oral contraceptives), and pregnancy. Histology shows septal panniculitis without vasculitis. Treatment addresses underlying cause and includes NSAIDs.<br><br>Candida (option B) does not typically cause erythema nodosum; scabies (option C) and HSV (option D) are not associated with the panniculitis pattern, all distinct from the tuberculosis-erythema nodosum association.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Most important measure in treating infestations',o:['Exercise','Sun exposure','Vitamins','Treat close contacts'],a:3,e:`The most important measure in treating infestations is treating close contacts; simultaneous treatment of household members and intimate partners prevents reinfection from untreated reservoirs after primary therapy.<br><br>All close contacts should be treated empirically even if asymptomatic in scabies and pediculosis. Bedding, clothing, and towels require hot wash. Failure to treat contacts is the leading cause of treatment failure clinically.<br><br>Exercise (option A), sun exposure (option B), and vitamins (option C) are not principal infestation management measures, none addressing the reinfection from untreated contacts which is the key clinical pitfall.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'A teenager presents with comedones, papules and pustules over face. Primary pathogenic factor in acne vulgaris is',o:['Viral infection','Sweat gland blockage','Increased sebum production','Autoimmune reaction'],a:2,e:`The primary pathogenic factor in acne vulgaris is increased sebum production; androgen-stimulated sebaceous gland hyperactivity combines with follicular hyperkeratinisation and Cutibacterium acnes proliferation.<br><br>Inflammation completes the four-factor pathogenesis. Comedones (open and closed), papules, pustules, and nodulocystic lesions develop. Severity grading guides treatment intensity from topical to systemic agents in adolescent and adult patients.<br><br>Viral infection (option A) is unrelated to acne; sweat gland blockage (option B) is miliaria not acne; autoimmune reaction (option D) describes other dermatoses, none being the primary acne mechanism in pubertal patients.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'The bacterium most associated with acne vulgaris is',o:['Cutibacterium acnes','Staphylococcus epidermidis','Streptococcus pyogenes','Malassezia furfur'],a:0,e:`Cutibacterium acnes is the bacterium most associated with acne vulgaris; this Gram-positive anaerobic rod (formerly Propionibacterium) colonises pilosebaceous units and contributes to inflammatory acne.<br><br>C. acnes hydrolyses sebum triglycerides releasing free fatty acids and produces inflammatory mediators. Antibiotic therapy targets this organism but increasing resistance limits effectiveness; combination with benzoyl peroxide reduces resistance development clinically.<br><br>Staphylococcus epidermidis (option B) is normal flora; Streptococcus pyogenes (option C) causes impetigo; Malassezia furfur (option D) causes pityriasis versicolor, none being the principal acne organism specifically.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Open comedones are commonly called',o:['Nodules','Whiteheads','Cysts','Blackheads'],a:3,e:`Open comedones are commonly called blackheads; oxidation of sebum and accumulated cellular debris produces the characteristic dark colour at the open follicular orifice.<br><br>The dark colour is not dirt but oxidised lipid and pigmented compounds. Closed comedones are whiteheads with intact follicular roof. Both are non-inflammatory acne lesions preceding inflammatory papulopustular development typically.<br><br>Nodules (option A) are deep inflammatory lesions; whiteheads (option B) are closed comedones; cysts (option C) are large fluctuant lesions, none being the open comedone with characteristic dark surface oxidation.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'First line topical therapy for mild acne',o:['Oral isotretinoin','Topical benzoyl peroxide','Oral antibiotics','Systemic steroids'],a:1,e:`Topical benzoyl peroxide is first-line topical therapy for mild acne; this oxidising agent kills Cutibacterium acnes and has comedolytic and mild anti-inflammatory effects on lesions.<br><br>Strengths range from 2.5 to 10 percent. Combination with topical retinoids or antibiotics improves efficacy and reduces resistance. Side effects include dryness, irritation, and bleaching of clothing and bedding requiring patient education.<br><br>Oral isotretinoin (option A) is reserved for severe nodulocystic acne; oral antibiotics (option C) are used for moderate-severe disease; systemic steroids (option D) are not first-line, used only for acne fulminans rarely.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'A 16-year-old girl presents with inflammatory acne unresponsive to topical therapy. Next appropriate step',o:['Oral antibiotics','Antiviral therapy','Antifungal therapy','Phototherapy'],a:0,e:`Oral antibiotics are the next appropriate step for inflammatory acne unresponsive to topical therapy; tetracyclines (doxycycline, minocycline) reduce C. acnes counts and have anti-inflammatory effects.<br><br>Treatment course is 3-6 months. Combine with topical benzoyl peroxide to reduce antibiotic resistance development. Avoid in pregnancy and children under 8 years due to dental staining and skeletal effects respectively.<br><br>Antiviral therapy (option B) treats viral infections; antifungal therapy (option C) treats fungal disease; phototherapy (option D) is reserved for resistant cases, none being the standard next step after topical failure.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Severe nodulocystic acne drug of choice',o:['Clindamycin topical','Isotretinoin','Doxycycline','Salicylic acid'],a:1,e:`Isotretinoin is the drug of choice for severe nodulocystic acne; this oral retinoid reduces sebum production, follicular hyperkeratinisation, C. acnes counts, and inflammation through all four pathogenic mechanisms.<br><br>Course typically 4-6 months at cumulative dose of 120-150 mg/kg. Side effects include cheilitis, dry skin, elevated lipids, hepatic enzyme elevation, and depression. Strict pregnancy prevention is mandatory due to teratogenicity.<br><br>Topical clindamycin (option A) is for mild-moderate acne; doxycycline (option C) is oral antibiotic for moderate disease; salicylic acid (option D) is keratolytic for comedonal acne, none for severe nodulocystic.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient on isotretinoin must avoid pregnancy because of',o:['Neurotoxicity','Nephrotoxicity','Teratogenicity','Hepatotoxicity'],a:2,e:`Patients on isotretinoin must avoid pregnancy because of teratogenicity; isotretinoin causes severe craniofacial, cardiac, thymic, and CNS malformations even with brief first-trimester exposure during pregnancy.<br><br>Two effective contraceptive methods are mandatory from one month before through one month after treatment. Monthly pregnancy testing required. iPLEDGE program in some countries enforces strict prescribing protocols for risk minimisation.<br><br>Neurotoxicity (option A) is not the principal isotretinoin concern; nephrotoxicity (option B) is not characteristic; hepatotoxicity (option D) requires monitoring but is reversible, leaving teratogenicity as the dominant risk.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Pruritic erythematous lesions with vesicles and oozing most suggest',o:['Psoriasis','Acne','Lichen planus','Eczema'],a:3,e:`Eczema presents with pruritic erythematous lesions with vesicles and oozing; this term encompasses atopic dermatitis, contact dermatitis, and other inflammatory skin conditions sharing similar morphology.<br><br>Acute eczema features erythema, oedema, vesiculation, and oozing. Subacute lesions develop crusting and scaling. Chronic eczema produces lichenification from repeated scratching. Treatment includes emollients and topical corticosteroids.<br><br>Psoriasis (option A) shows well-demarcated plaques with silvery scale; acne (option B) features comedones and pustules; lichen planus (option C) has violaceous flat-topped papules, distinct from eczema morphology.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The most common type of eczema in children',o:['Contact dermatitis','Atopic dermatitis','Nummular eczema','Seborrheic dermatitis'],a:1,e:`Atopic dermatitis is the most common type of eczema in children; this chronic relapsing inflammatory dermatosis affects up to 20 percent of children and reflects barrier dysfunction with immune dysregulation.<br><br>Filaggrin mutations and Th2-skewed inflammation underlie pathogenesis. Distribution is age-dependent: face and extensors in infants, flexures in older children. Personal or family history of atopy (asthma, allergic rhinitis) common.<br><br>Contact dermatitis (option A) is exposure-related; nummular eczema (option C) features coin-shaped plaques; seborrhoeic dermatitis (option D) affects sebaceous areas, none being the principal childhood eczema entity.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Atopic dermatitis associated immunoglobulin',o:['IgE','IgM','IgG','IgA'],a:0,e:`Atopic dermatitis is associated with elevated IgE; Th2-skewed immune response promotes class switching to IgE production with secondary mast cell activation contributing to inflammation and pruritus.<br><br>Total IgE and specific IgE to common allergens are often elevated. The atopic march refers to progression from atopic dermatitis to asthma and allergic rhinitis. Filaggrin gene mutations contribute to barrier dysfunction.<br><br>IgM (option B) is involved in primary immune response; IgG (option C) mediates secondary humoral immunity; IgA (option D) is mucosal antibody, none being the immunoglobulin class characteristically elevated in atopic dermatitis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Flexural lichenification in a child with history of asthma indicates',o:['Psoriasis','Fungal infection','Lichen planus','Atopic dermatitis'],a:3,e:`Flexural lichenification in a child with asthma history indicates atopic dermatitis; the atopic triad of eczema, asthma, and allergic rhinitis reflects shared Th2-mediated immune pathophysiology.<br><br>Lichenification develops from chronic scratching, producing thickened skin with accentuated markings. Common in antecubital and popliteal fossae, posterior neck. Personal or family history of atopy supports diagnosis. Treatment includes emollients and topical corticosteroids.<br><br>Psoriasis (option A) has silvery scaling plaques on extensors; fungal infection (option B) shows central clearing; lichen planus (option C) has violaceous polygonal papules, all distinct from atopic flexural lichenification.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'First line treatment of eczema flare',o:['Oral antivirals','Retinoids','Topical corticosteroids','Oral antifungals'],a:2,e:`Topical corticosteroids are first-line treatment of eczema flare; potent steroids reduce inflammation and pruritus rapidly during acute exacerbations.<br><br>Choice of potency depends on severity, location, and patient age. Use for limited duration to avoid skin atrophy. Calcineurin inhibitors (tacrolimus, pimecrolimus) are alternatives for face, eyelids, and steroid-sparing maintenance therapy.<br><br>Oral antivirals (option A) treat herpes infection; retinoids (option B) treat acne and psoriasis; oral antifungals (option D) treat fungal infection, none being effective for inflammatory eczema flares specifically.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Chronic scratching in eczema leads to',o:['Lichenification','Comedones','Koebner phenomenon','Scaling plaques'],a:0,e:`Chronic scratching in eczema leads to lichenification; repeated mechanical trauma thickens the epidermis and accentuates skin markings, producing leathery plaques characteristic of long-standing eczema.<br><br>The itch-scratch cycle perpetuates inflammation and lichenification. Breaking the cycle requires addressing pruritus with antihistamines, emollients, and corticosteroids alongside behavioural modification. Lichen simplex chronicus represents lichenification from neurodermatitis primarily.<br><br>Comedones (option B) are acne lesions; Koebner phenomenon (option C) is lesion development at trauma sites in psoriasis; scaling plaques (option D) characterise psoriasis, all distinct from eczema lichenification.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Well demarcated erythematous plaques with silvery scale suggest',o:['Eczema','Tinea','Lichen planus','Psoriasis'],a:3,e:`Well-demarcated erythematous plaques with silvery scale suggest psoriasis; this chronic inflammatory disorder produces characteristic scaling plaques on extensor surfaces, scalp, and other classical sites.<br><br>Auspitz sign shows pinpoint bleeding on scale removal reflecting capillary loops in dermal papillae. Koebner phenomenon describes lesion development at trauma sites. T cell-mediated inflammation drives keratinocyte hyperproliferation and parakeratosis.<br><br>Eczema (option A) is poorly demarcated and pruritic; tinea (option B) shows central clearing; lichen planus (option C) features violaceous flat-topped papules, none matching the silvery-scale plaques of psoriasis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Auspitz sign refers to',o:['Central clearing','Pinpoint bleeding on scale removal','Satellite lesions','Wickham striae'],a:1,e:`Auspitz sign refers to pinpoint bleeding on scale removal; this characteristic finding in psoriasis reflects elongated dermal papillae with prominent capillaries near the epidermal surface.<br><br>The sign supports clinical diagnosis of psoriasis when present. Removal of the silvery scale exposes the thinned suprapapillary epidermis and bleeds from underlying capillary loops, producing the Auspitz phenomenon characteristically.<br><br>Central clearing (option A) characterises tinea infection; satellite lesions (option C) suggest candidiasis; Wickham striae (option D) are reticulate white lines of lichen planus, none being the Auspitz pinpoint bleeding sign.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Koebner phenomenon seen in',o:['Urticaria','Acne','Psoriasis','Scabies'],a:2,e:`Koebner phenomenon is seen in psoriasis; new lesions develop at sites of skin trauma in active disease, reflecting the disease propensity for development at locations of injury.<br><br>Other Koebner-positive conditions include lichen planus, vitiligo, and warts. Surgery, scratching, sunburn, and other trauma may trigger new lesions. The phenomenon indicates active disease and suggests caution with cosmetic procedures clinically.<br><br>Urticaria (option A) shows wheals at non-traumatic sites; acne (option B) is follicular; scabies (option D) is infestation, none demonstrating the Koebner isomorphic response to skin trauma in active disease.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Most common site of psoriasis',o:['Extensor surfaces','Palms only','Flexures','Face'],a:0,e:`The most common site of psoriasis is extensor surfaces; elbows, knees, scalp, and lumbosacral area are typical locations producing the characteristic well-demarcated silvery-scaled plaques.<br><br>Inverse psoriasis affects flexures with smooth erythematous plaques. Scalp psoriasis often presents with thick adherent scale. Nail involvement (pitting, onycholysis) and joint involvement (psoriatic arthritis) accompany skin disease in many patients.<br><br>Palms only (option B) describes palmoplantar psoriasis variant; flexures (option C) is inverse psoriasis; face (option D) is uncommon site, none being the characteristic principal distribution of plaque psoriasis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Nail pitting indicates',o:['Acne','Eczema','Psoriasis','Lichen simplex'],a:2,e:`Nail pitting indicates psoriasis; punctate depressions on the nail plate result from psoriatic involvement of the nail matrix producing focal parakeratosis that sloughs leaving pits.<br><br>Other psoriatic nail changes include onycholysis (separation), oil drops (yellow-brown patches), subungual hyperkeratosis, and salmon patches. Up to 50 percent of psoriasis patients have nail involvement, more common in psoriatic arthritis.<br><br>Acne (option A) does not affect nails; eczema (option B) may produce nail dystrophy but not classic pitting; lichen simplex (option D) does not characteristically pit nails, leaving psoriasis as the principal cause.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Drug useful in severe psoriasis',o:['Fluconazole','Acyclovir','Ivermectin','Methotrexate'],a:3,e:`Methotrexate is useful in severe psoriasis; this folate antagonist reduces keratinocyte proliferation and immune cell activity, producing improvement in extensive plaque and pustular psoriasis.<br><br>Weekly oral or subcutaneous dosing with folic acid supplementation. Hepatotoxicity, bone marrow suppression, and pulmonary toxicity require monitoring. Cyclosporine, retinoids, biologics (TNF inhibitors, IL-17, IL-23 antagonists) are alternatives in resistant disease.<br><br>Fluconazole (option A) is antifungal; acyclovir (option B) is antiviral; ivermectin (option C) is antiparasitic, none being effective immunomodulatory therapy for severe psoriasis with extensive disease.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Purple polygonal pruritic papules suggest',o:['Psoriasis','Lichen planus','Acne','Impetigo'],a:1,e:`Purple polygonal pruritic papules suggest lichen planus; this T cell-mediated inflammatory disorder produces characteristic violaceous flat-topped papules on flexor surfaces and oral mucosa.<br><br>Wickham striae are fine reticulate white lines visible on papules. Sites include wrists, forearms, ankles, lower back, and oral mucosa. Hepatitis C is associated. Treatment includes topical or systemic corticosteroids in symptomatic disease.<br><br>Psoriasis (option A) has silvery scale on erythematous base; acne (option C) features comedones and pustules; impetigo (option D) shows honey-coloured crusts, none being the violaceous polygonal pattern of lichen planus.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Wickham striae seen in',o:['Vitiligo','Psoriasis','Lichen planus','Eczema'],a:2,e:`Wickham striae are seen in lichen planus; these fine reticulate or lacy white lines on the surface of violaceous papules and oral mucosal lesions are characteristic clinical findings.<br><br>Wickham striae reflect hypergranulosis and hyperkeratosis on histology. Oral lichen planus may show predominantly Wickham striae without papules. Symptomatic erosive oral lichen planus carries small risk of squamous cell carcinoma.<br><br>Vitiligo (option A) shows depigmented patches without striae; psoriasis (option B) has silvery scale; eczema (option D) is poorly demarcated, none being the Wickham striae of lichen planus specifically diagnostic.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Lichen planus commonly involves',o:['Oral mucosa','Palms only','Nails only','Scalp only'],a:0,e:`Lichen planus commonly involves the oral mucosa; up to 70 percent of cutaneous lichen planus patients have concurrent oral involvement with reticulate white lines or erosive lesions on buccal mucosa.<br><br>Oral lichen planus subtypes include reticular (Wickham striae), atrophic, erosive, and bullous forms. Erosive disease carries small but established malignant transformation risk to oral squamous cell carcinoma over years.<br><br>Palms only (option B), nails only (option C), and scalp only (option D) are not the typical predominant distribution patterns, leaving oral mucosa as a uniquely common involvement site in lichen planus.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A 28-year-old presents with violaceous papules on wrist after trauma at same site. Phenomenon',o:['Auspitz sign','Koebner phenomenon','Nikolsky sign','Darier sign'],a:1,e:`This Koebner phenomenon describes new lichen planus lesions developing at the site of skin trauma; the isomorphic response is characteristic of active lichen planus alongside psoriasis and vitiligo.<br><br>Surgery, scratching, friction, and other trauma trigger new lesions in active disease. The phenomenon suggests immunological priming for lesion development at any disturbed skin site. Avoidance of skin trauma during active disease is prudent.<br><br>Auspitz sign (option A) is pinpoint bleeding on psoriatic scale removal; Nikolsky sign (option C) is epidermal sliding in pemphigus; Darier sign (option D) is wheal formation in mastocytosis, all distinct phenomena.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'First line therapy for localized lichen planus',o:['Retinoids','Antivirals','Antibiotics','Topical steroids'],a:3,e:`Topical steroids are first-line therapy for localised lichen planus; potent corticosteroids reduce T cell-mediated inflammation and improve symptoms in cutaneous and mucosal disease.<br><br>Calcineurin inhibitors are alternatives for oral and genital involvement. Oral or intramuscular steroids treat extensive disease. Phototherapy and oral retinoids are reserved for refractory cases. Most cutaneous disease resolves within 1-2 years.<br><br>Retinoids (option A) are second-line for refractory disease; antivirals (option B) treat viral infection; antibiotics (option C) treat bacterial infection, none being first-line for inflammatory autoimmune lichen planus.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Acne scars form due to',o:['Sweat gland blockage','Pigment loss','Dermal collagen destruction','Increased keratinization only'],a:2,e:`Acne scars form due to dermal collagen destruction; inflammatory acne lesions damage dermal collagen producing atrophic (icepick, boxcar, rolling) or hypertrophic scars after resolution.<br><br>Atrophic scars are most common reflecting net collagen loss. Hypertrophic and keloid scars reflect excessive collagen deposition. Treatment includes laser, microneedling, dermal fillers, subcision, and chemical peels in cosmetically motivated patients.<br><br>Sweat gland blockage (option A) describes miliaria; pigment loss (option B) is post-inflammatory hypopigmentation not scarring; increased keratinisation only (option D) describes comedone formation, none being the dermal mechanism of true scarring.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with greasy scales over scalp and nasolabial folds likely has',o:['Seborrheic dermatitis','Tinea corporis','Psoriasis','Acne'],a:0,e:`Greasy scales over scalp and nasolabial folds suggest seborrhoeic dermatitis; Malassezia yeasts proliferate in sebum-rich areas producing characteristic erythematous patches with yellow greasy scaling.<br><br>Other classic sites include eyebrows, paranasal areas, ears, and chest. Treatment includes ketoconazole shampoo, antifungal creams, and topical corticosteroids for inflammation. HIV and Parkinson disease predispose to severe seborrhoeic dermatitis clinically.<br><br>Tinea corporis (option B) shows annular lesion with central clearing; psoriasis (option C) has silvery scale on extensors; acne (option D) features comedones and pustules, none matching seborrhoeic morphology.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Main trigger in atopic dermatitis',o:['Drug allergy only','Barrier dysfunction','Bacterial toxin','Viral infection'],a:3,e:`The main trigger in atopic dermatitis is barrier dysfunction; filaggrin gene mutations and lipid abnormalities impair stratum corneum function, allowing allergen penetration and Th2 immune activation.<br><br>Loss of filaggrin reduces natural moisturising factor and increases skin pH. Skin becomes susceptible to Staphylococcus aureus colonisation and inflammation. Restoring barrier function with emollients is foundational to management.<br><br>Drug allergy only (option A) is contact dermatitis; bacterial toxin (option C) is staphylococcal; viral infection (option D) may complicate eczema but is not the primary trigger, leaving barrier dysfunction as fundamental.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Psoriasis pathogenesis involves',o:['Fungal infection','T cell mediated inflammation','IgE hypersensitivity','Mite infestation'],a:1,e:`Psoriasis pathogenesis involves T cell-mediated inflammation; activated Th1 and Th17 cells produce cytokines (TNF-alpha, IL-17, IL-23) driving keratinocyte hyperproliferation and parakeratosis.<br><br>Genetic susceptibility (HLA-Cw6 association) and environmental triggers (infection, drugs, stress) initiate disease. Modern biologic therapies targeting TNF, IL-17, and IL-23 axes have transformed management of moderate to severe psoriasis substantially.<br><br>Fungal infection (option A) is not psoriatic mechanism; IgE hypersensitivity (option C) characterises atopic dermatitis; mite infestation (option D) is scabies, none being the immune mechanism of psoriasis pathogenesis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Lichen planus associated with',o:['Hepatitis A','Hepatitis C','Tuberculosis','HIV only'],a:3,e:`Lichen planus is associated with hepatitis C; HCV infection is found in higher prevalence among lichen planus patients, particularly with oral involvement, in many populations.<br><br>Hepatitis screening is reasonable in patients with lichen planus, especially erosive oral disease. Other associations include drug-induced lichenoid reactions and graft-versus-host disease. Treatment of underlying HCV may improve lichen planus activity in some patients.<br><br>Hepatitis A (option A) is not associated; tuberculosis (option C) is not linked; HIV only (option D) is not the principal association, leaving hepatitis C as the established viral association in lichen planus.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with erythrodermic psoriasis complication risk',o:['Polycythemia','Hypoglycemia','Hypothermia and fluid loss','Hypercalcemia'],a:2,e:`Erythrodermic psoriasis carries risk of hypothermia and fluid loss; widespread cutaneous inflammation impairs barrier function producing significant transepidermal water loss and impaired thermoregulation.<br><br>High-output cardiac failure may also develop from increased cutaneous blood flow. Patients require hospitalisation, fluid replacement, temperature management, and aggressive psoriasis treatment. Mortality in untreated severe cases reaches 10-20 percent historically.<br><br>Polycythaemia (option A) is not a complication; hypoglycaemia (option B) is not characteristic; hypercalcaemia (option D) is not typical, leaving fluid loss and hypothermia as principal life-threatening complications of erythroderma.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'A teenager with moderate acne and inflammatory lesions on chest and back not responding to doxycycline. Next best step',o:['Topical antifungal','UV phototherapy','Antiviral therapy','Oral isotretinoin'],a:1,e:`Moderate acne unresponsive to doxycycline warrants oral isotretinoin; severe inflammatory acne or treatment failure with oral antibiotics indicates progression to systemic retinoid therapy.<br><br>Isotretinoin reduces sebum, comedogenesis, C. acnes counts, and inflammation. Strict pregnancy prevention and laboratory monitoring required. Course typically 4-6 months with cumulative dose of 120-150 mg/kg producing prolonged remission in most.<br><br>Topical antifungal (option A) is not acne therapy; UV phototherapy (option B) is not first-line for inflammatory acne; antiviral therapy (option C) treats viral infection, none being the appropriate next step after antibiotic failure.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'A child with severe itching, flexural eczema, allergic rhinitis and asthma has underlying',o:['Atopy','Infection','Nutritional deficiency','Malignancy'],a:0,e:`A child with severe itching, flexural eczema, allergic rhinitis, and asthma has atopy; this triad of atopic conditions reflects shared Th2-mediated immune pathophysiology with elevated IgE.<br><br>Filaggrin gene mutations contribute to barrier dysfunction. The atopic march describes progression from atopic dermatitis in infancy to asthma and allergic rhinitis later. Family history of atopy supports diagnosis.<br><br>Infection (option B) does not produce the atopic triad; nutritional deficiency (option C) is not characteristic; malignancy (option D) does not present with eczema-asthma-rhinitis combination, leaving atopy as the unifying diagnosis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A middle-aged patient has chronic plaques on elbows and knees with nail pitting and arthritis. Diagnosis',o:['Osteoarthritis','Rheumatoid arthritis','Gout','Psoriatic arthritis'],a:1,e:`Chronic plaques on elbows and knees with nail pitting and arthritis suggest psoriatic arthritis; this seronegative spondyloarthropathy combines cutaneous psoriasis with inflammatory joint disease.<br><br>Patterns include distal interphalangeal arthritis, asymmetric oligoarthritis, symmetric polyarthritis (RA-like), arthritis mutilans, and spondylitis. Up to 30 percent of psoriasis patients develop arthritis. Treatment includes NSAIDs, DMARDs, and biologics (anti-TNF, IL-17 inhibitors).<br><br>Osteoarthritis (option A) lacks skin and nail features; rheumatoid arthritis (option B) is symmetric without psoriasis; gout (option C) features tophi and crystals, none combining the cutaneous-articular features here.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient develops violaceous oral lesions with burning sensation and white lacy lines. Diagnosis',o:['Candidiasis','Leukoplakia','Lichen planus','Aphthous ulcer'],a:2,e:`Violaceous oral lesions with burning sensation and white lacy lines suggest lichen planus; reticular Wickham striae on buccal mucosa accompanied by erosive components define oral lichen planus.<br><br>Subtypes include reticular, atrophic, erosive, and bullous forms. Erosive disease carries small malignant transformation risk to oral squamous cell carcinoma. Treatment includes topical corticosteroids and calcineurin inhibitors for symptomatic disease.<br><br>Candidiasis (option A) shows white plaques scraping off easily; leukoplakia (option B) is white plaques without lacy pattern; aphthous ulcer (option D) shows discrete painful ulcers, distinct from lichen planus.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A child with weeping erythematous lesions behind knees worsened by wool clothing likely has',o:['Scabies','Atopic eczema','Psoriasis','Acne'],a:3,e:`A child with weeping erythematous lesions behind knees worsened by wool clothing has atopic eczema; flexural distribution and irritant trigger sensitivity are characteristic of atopic dermatitis pathology.<br><br>Other features include intense pruritus, lichenification from chronic scratching, and personal or family atopy history. Treatment includes emollients, topical corticosteroids during flares, and trigger avoidance. Wool and synthetic fabrics commonly aggravate symptoms.<br><br>Scabies (option A) shows web-space burrows and family clustering; psoriasis (option C) features silvery scale on extensors; acne (option D) is follicular, none matching the flexural eczema pattern in this child.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with sudden worsening psoriasis after steroid withdrawal has',o:['Rebound flare','Infection','Drug allergy','Malignancy'],a:0,e:`Sudden worsening of psoriasis after steroid withdrawal indicates rebound flare; abrupt cessation of systemic corticosteroids triggers severe disease exacerbation, potentially producing erythroderma or pustular psoriasis.<br><br>Systemic corticosteroids should be avoided in psoriasis or tapered very gradually if used. Topical steroid withdrawal may also trigger rebound. Alternative immunomodulators including methotrexate, cyclosporine, or biologics provide steroid-sparing maintenance therapy.<br><br>Infection (option B) may flare psoriasis but is not steroid-related; drug allergy (option C) presents differently; malignancy (option D) is not typical, leaving steroid rebound as the recognised post-withdrawal phenomenon.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'An adult with itchy coin-shaped plaques on limbs most likely',o:['Psoriasis','Nummular eczema','Acne','Lichen planus'],a:2,e:`Itchy coin-shaped plaques on limbs in adults most likely represent nummular eczema; well-demarcated round or oval erythematous plaques with vesicles, oozing, and crusting characterise this morphology.<br><br>Distinct from atopic dermatitis distribution. Triggers include xerosis, irritants, and bacterial colonisation. Treatment includes emollients, topical corticosteroids, and treatment of secondary bacterial infection. Chronic course with periodic exacerbations is typical.<br><br>Psoriasis (option A) shows silvery scale not coin-shaped pruritic morphology; acne (option C) is follicular; lichen planus (option D) features violaceous papules, none matching the discoid eczematous pattern.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with generalized pustular psoriasis risk',o:['Hypertension','Diabetes','Migraine','Sepsis'],a:3,e:`Generalised pustular psoriasis carries risk of sepsis; widespread sterile pustules and breakdown of skin barrier predispose to bacterial superinfection and systemic infection requiring urgent care.<br><br>Other complications include high-output cardiac failure, fluid and electrolyte loss, hypothermia, and hepatic dysfunction. Hospitalisation, supportive care, and aggressive psoriasis treatment with cyclosporine or biologics required for life-threatening flares clinically.<br><br>Hypertension (option A), diabetes (option B), and migraine (option C) are not principal acute complications, leaving sepsis from skin barrier disruption as the major life-threatening risk in generalised pustular disease.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Hypertrophic lichen planus most commonly affects',o:['Face','Palms','Shins','Scalp'],a:0,e:`Hypertrophic lichen planus most commonly affects the shins; thickened verrucous plaques with intense pruritus develop on anterior lower legs and dorsal feet, often persisting for years.<br><br>This variant is more chronic than classical lichen planus and may resemble lichen simplex chronicus. Treatment is challenging; potent topical or intralesional corticosteroids, retinoids, or phototherapy may be effective in some patients.<br><br>Face (option A) is uncommon site; palms (option B) characterise palmar lichen planus variant; scalp (option D) shows lichen planopilaris with scarring alopecia, none being the principal hypertrophic site.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with acne worsened by cosmetics has',o:['Folliculitis','Acne cosmetica','Milia','Rosacea'],a:1,e:`Acne worsened by cosmetics is acne cosmetica; comedogenic ingredients in cosmetic and skincare products occlude follicles producing comedonal acne in cosmetic application areas.<br><br>Avoidance of comedogenic products and use of non-comedogenic alternatives addresses the trigger. Heavy occlusive moisturisers, oil-based foundations, and certain hair products commonly contribute. Resolution occurs within weeks to months of trigger removal.<br><br>Folliculitis (option A) is bacterial follicular infection; milia (option C) are keratin-filled cysts; rosacea (option D) features facial erythema and papules without comedones, none being cosmetic-induced acne specifically.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with eczema develops honey colored crusts. Complication',o:['Malignancy','Secondary bacterial infection','Fungal infection','Viral infection'],a:3,e:`Honey-coloured crusts on eczema indicate secondary bacterial infection; Staphylococcus aureus colonisation and superinfection of disrupted skin barrier produces impetiginised eczema.<br><br>Treatment includes topical mupirocin or oral antibiotics targeting S. aureus alongside continued eczema management. Excoriations from intense pruritus break the barrier facilitating colonisation. Atopic dermatitis patients have elevated S. aureus carriage rates.<br><br>Malignancy (option A) does not present with honey crusts; viral infection (option D) typical Kaposi varicelliform shows monomorphic vesicles not crusts; fungal infection (option C) shows scaling not honey-coloured crusts.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'A psoriatic patient develops joint stiffness in morning >1 hour indicates',o:['Gout','Osteoarthritis','Psoriatic arthritis','Septic arthritis'],a:2,e:`Morning joint stiffness over 1 hour in psoriatic patient indicates psoriatic arthritis; inflammatory pattern with prolonged morning stiffness improving with activity differs from osteoarthritis.<br><br>Common patterns include distal interphalangeal arthritis, asymmetric oligoarthritis, RA-like polyarthritis, mutilans, and spondylitis. Treatment includes NSAIDs, methotrexate, leflunomide, and biologics (anti-TNF, IL-17 inhibitors) targeting joint and skin disease together.<br><br>Gout (option A) features acute monoarthritis with crystals; osteoarthritis (option B) has stiffness under 30 minutes; septic arthritis (option D) presents acutely with fever, distinct from chronic inflammatory psoriatic arthritis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with flat topped papules on wrists intensely pruritic with pigmentation after healing has',o:['Lichen planus','Acne','Eczema','Psoriasis'],a:1,e:`Flat-topped pruritic papules on wrists with post-inflammatory pigmentation suggest lichen planus; the violaceous polygonal papules with Wickham striae resolve leaving characteristic hyperpigmentation in many patients.<br><br>Common sites include flexor wrists, ankles, lower back, and oral mucosa. Hepatitis C is associated. Treatment includes topical or systemic corticosteroids. Most cutaneous disease resolves within 1-2 years with residual hyperpigmentation.<br><br>Acne (option B) is follicular; eczema (option C) is poorly demarcated and weeping; psoriasis (option D) has silvery scale, none matching the flat-topped violaceous polygonal lichen planus morphology.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A child with chronic eczema needs long term maintenance therapy',o:['Emollients','Antifungals','Antibiotics','Antivirals'],a:0,e:`Long-term maintenance therapy for chronic eczema is emollients; restoring barrier function with regular liberal moisturiser application reduces flare frequency and severity in atopic dermatitis.<br><br>Emollients should be applied at least twice daily, particularly after bathing. Different formulations (creams, ointments, lotions) suit different sites and seasons. Trigger avoidance and stress management complement emollient therapy in maintenance.<br><br>Antifungals (option B) are not maintenance for eczema; antibiotics (option C) treat infection not maintenance; antivirals (option D) treat viral infection, none being chronic maintenance therapy for atopic dermatitis.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with psoriasis treated with UVB therapy mechanism',o:['Immunosuppression of T cells','Sebum reduction','Bacterial killing','Collagen stimulation'],a:1,e:`UVB therapy in psoriasis works through immunosuppression of T cells; UVB induces apoptosis of skin-infiltrating T lymphocytes and reduces inflammatory cytokine production, improving psoriatic lesions.<br><br>Narrowband UVB (311-313 nm) is preferred over broadband for efficacy and safety. Treatment 2-3 times weekly produces clearance over 8-12 weeks in many patients. Long-term cumulative dose increases skin cancer risk slightly.<br><br>Sebum reduction (option B) is unrelated; bacterial killing (option C) is not the principal mechanism; collagen stimulation (option D) describes other phototherapy applications, leaving immunosuppression as the psoriatic mechanism.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'A young adult with facial flushing and papules but no comedones likely has',o:['Acne vulgaris','Psoriasis','Rosacea','Lichen planus'],a:2,e:`A young adult with facial flushing and papules without comedones likely has rosacea; this chronic inflammatory facial dermatosis features erythema, telangiectasia, papules, and pustules in the central face.<br><br>Subtypes include erythematotelangiectatic, papulopustular, phymatous (rhinophyma), and ocular rosacea. Triggers include heat, alcohol, spicy food, sunlight, and stress. Treatment includes topical metronidazole, ivermectin, oral tetracyclines, and trigger avoidance.<br><br>Acne vulgaris (option A) features comedones; psoriasis (option B) has scaling plaques; lichen planus (option D) shows violaceous papules, none matching the comedone-free papulopustular facial pattern of rosacea.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with severe itching worse at night and thickened skin folds due to chronic eczema',o:['Tinea','Lichen simplex chronicus','Acne','Psoriasis'],a:3,e:`Severe nocturnal itching with thickened skin folds from chronic eczema describes lichen simplex chronicus; the itch-scratch cycle produces lichenified plaques with accentuated skin markings.<br><br>Common sites include nape of neck, ankles, and anogenital region. Breaking the itch-scratch cycle requires potent topical corticosteroids, occlusion, and behavioural modification to prevent further mechanical trauma to the skin.<br><br>Tinea (option A) shows central clearing; acne (option C) is follicular; psoriasis (option D) has silvery scale on extensors, none matching the lichenified neurodermatitis pattern of lichen simplex chronicus.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A psoriasis patient with sudden hypocalcemia and widespread pustules has',o:['Generalized pustular psoriasis','Drug rash','Viral exanthem','Acne fulminans'],a:0,e:`Sudden hypocalcaemia with widespread pustules in psoriatic patient indicates generalised pustular psoriasis; severe systemic flare disrupts barrier function and may produce metabolic complications including hypocalcaemia.<br><br>Other complications include high-output cardiac failure, fluid loss, hypothermia, hepatic dysfunction, and sepsis from secondary bacterial infection. Hospitalisation, supportive care, and aggressive psoriasis treatment with cyclosporine or biologics required urgently.<br><br>Drug rash (option B) lacks the systemic pustular pattern; viral exanthem (option C) is morbilliform; acne fulminans (option D) is severe acne not pustular psoriasis, leaving generalised pustular as the diagnosis.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with oral lichen planus risk increases for',o:['Basal cell carcinoma','Squamous cell carcinoma','Sarcoma','Melanoma'],a:2,e:`Oral lichen planus increases risk for squamous cell carcinoma; chronic erosive oral disease carries small but established malignant transformation risk requiring surveillance.<br><br>Erosive and atrophic subtypes carry highest risk. Risk increases with smoking, alcohol use, and HCV co-infection. Regular oral examination and biopsy of suspicious changing lesions enable early detection of malignant transformation in chronic disease.<br><br>Basal cell carcinoma (option A) is sun-related and not oral; sarcoma (option C) is mesenchymal; melanoma (option D) is melanocytic, none being the principal malignancy associated with oral lichen planus over time.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'A severe acne patient with fever, arthralgia and ulcerative nodules likely has',o:['Acne fulminans','Folliculitis','Rosacea','Impetigo'],a:0,e:`Severe acne with fever, arthralgia, and ulcerative nodules indicates acne fulminans; this rare severe form features systemic symptoms with crusted ulcerative inflammatory nodules in young males predominantly.<br><br>Systemic corticosteroids combined with isotretinoin produce response. NSAIDs help arthralgia. Inflammatory markers and bone scintigraphy may show systemic involvement (SAPHO syndrome variant). Distinct from acne conglobata which lacks systemic features clinically.<br><br>Folliculitis (option B) lacks systemic features; rosacea (option C) is facial without ulceration; impetigo (option D) is superficial bacterial, none matching the systemic acne fulminans pattern in young males.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'The level of blister in pemphigus vulgaris is',o:['Dermal','Subepidermal','Suprabasal intraepidermal','Subcorneal'],a:3,e:`Pemphigus vulgaris produces suprabasal intraepidermal blister; autoantibodies against desmoglein-3 disrupt desmosomal adhesion just above the basal layer, producing flaccid intraepidermal cleavage.<br><br>Direct immunofluorescence shows IgG deposition in fishnet pattern around keratinocytes. Tzanck smear reveals acantholytic cells. Mortality untreated reaches 75 percent; treatment with systemic corticosteroids and rituximab now produces good outcomes.<br><br>Dermal (option A) blisters occur in epidermolysis bullosa acquisita; subepidermal (option B) blisters characterise pemphigoid; subcorneal (option D) characterises pemphigus foliaceus, all distinct from suprabasal pemphigus vulgaris cleavage.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Autoantibodies in pemphigus vulgaris target',o:['Hemidesmosomes','Integrins','Desmoglein 3','Collagen IV'],a:1,e:`Pemphigus vulgaris autoantibodies target desmoglein 3; this transmembrane cadherin in desmosomes maintains keratinocyte adhesion in suprabasal epidermis, and antibody binding produces acantholysis with intraepidermal blistering.<br><br>Pemphigus foliaceus autoantibodies target desmoglein 1, located higher in epidermis producing subcorneal cleavage. Mucosal-dominant pemphigus targets only desmoglein 3, while mucocutaneous disease targets both desmogleins 1 and 3.<br><br>Hemidesmosomes (option A) are bullous pemphigoid targets; integrins (option B) mediate cell-matrix adhesion; collagen IV (option D) is in basement membrane, none being the desmoglein cadherin target of pemphigus vulgaris.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Nikolsky sign positive in',o:['Bullous pemphigoid','Pemphigus vulgaris','Dermatitis herpetiformis','Porphyria cutanea tarda'],a:2,e:`Nikolsky sign is positive in pemphigus vulgaris; lateral pressure on apparently normal skin produces epidermal sliding due to acantholysis from desmoglein-3 autoantibodies.<br><br>Direct immunofluorescence shows IgG deposition in fishnet intercellular pattern. Tzanck smear reveals acantholytic cells. Treatment with systemic corticosteroids, immunosuppressants, and rituximab has transformed prognosis from frequently fatal to manageable chronic disease.<br><br>Bullous pemphigoid (option A) has negative Nikolsky sign with tense bullae; dermatitis herpetiformis (option C) shows grouped vesicles; porphyria cutanea tarda (option D) features photosensitive blisters, all Nikolsky-negative.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Bullous pemphigoid blister is',o:['Tense subepidermal','Pustular','Flaccid','Intraepidermal'],a:3,e:`Bullous pemphigoid blister is tense subepidermal; autoantibodies against hemidesmosome proteins BP180 and BP230 produce cleavage at the dermo-epidermal junction with thick blister roof.<br><br>Direct immunofluorescence shows linear IgG and C3 deposition along the basement membrane zone. Salt-split skin testing localises antibodies to the epidermal side. Treatment includes systemic corticosteroids and steroid-sparing immunosuppressants like azathioprine.<br><br>Pustular (option B) describes purulent collections; flaccid (option C) characterises pemphigus vulgaris; intraepidermal (option D) is also pemphigus, all distinct from the tense subepidermal pemphigoid blister architecture clinically.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Dermatitis herpetiformis associated with',o:['Iron deficiency','Tuberculosis','Diabetes mellitus','Gluten sensitivity'],a:0,e:`Dermatitis herpetiformis is associated with gluten sensitivity; this cutaneous manifestation of celiac disease responds to gluten-free diet alongside medical therapy with dapsone.<br><br>Granular IgA deposition in dermal papillae on direct immunofluorescence is diagnostic. Most patients have associated celiac disease histology even without gastrointestinal symptoms. HLA-DQ2 and DQ8 alleles confer genetic susceptibility to both conditions.<br><br>Iron deficiency (option A) is non-specific; tuberculosis (option B) is not associated; diabetes mellitus (option C) is not the link, leaving gluten sensitivity as the established autoimmune association of dermatitis herpetiformis.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Immunoglobulin deposited in dermatitis herpetiformis',o:['IgA','IgG','IgE','IgM'],a:1,e:`Dermatitis herpetiformis features IgA deposition in dermal papillae; granular IgA on direct immunofluorescence in papillary dermis distinguishes this autoimmune disease from other immunobullous disorders.<br><br>Tissue transglutaminase autoantibodies link skin and gut disease. HLA-DQ2 and DQ8 alleles confer genetic susceptibility. Strict gluten-free diet allows reduction or discontinuation of dapsone over 6-24 months in compliant patients.<br><br>IgG (option B) is in pemphigoid and pemphigus; IgE (option C) mediates atopic disease; IgM (option D) is acute response immunoglobulin, none being the dermatitis herpetiformis immunoglobulin specifically.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'First line treatment dermatitis herpetiformis',o:['Acyclovir','Steroids','Methotrexate','Dapsone'],a:0,e:`First-line treatment of dermatitis herpetiformis is dapsone; this sulfone drug rapidly relieves intense pruritus through inhibition of neutrophil chemotaxis and other anti-inflammatory mechanisms.<br><br>Onset of relief is within hours. G6PD screening required before initiation due to haemolysis risk. Methaemoglobinaemia and agranulocytosis are other adverse effects. Strict gluten-free diet allows dose reduction over months.<br><br>Acyclovir (option A) is antiviral; steroids (option B) are not first-line for DH; methotrexate (option C) is for severe psoriasis, none being first-line for the neutrophil-mediated dermatitis herpetiformis blistering.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Vitiligo characterized by loss of',o:['Keratinocytes','Melanocytes','Fibroblasts','Langerhans cells'],a:2,e:`Vitiligo is characterised by loss of melanocytes; autoimmune destruction of melanocytes by cytotoxic CD8 T cells produces depigmented patches with sharp borders, often appearing in symmetric distribution.<br><br>Wood lamp examination accentuates lesions. Associated autoimmune diseases include thyroid disease, type 1 diabetes, and Addison disease. Treatment includes topical steroids, calcineurin inhibitors, phototherapy, and pigment cell transplantation in selected cases.<br><br>Keratinocytes (option A) are unaffected; fibroblasts (option C) are dermal cells; Langerhans cells (option D) are immune sentinels, none being the targeted cell population in autoimmune vitiligo pathogenesis specifically.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Wood lamp examination in vitiligo shows',o:['Blue white accentuation','Yellow fluorescence','Green fluorescence','Red fluorescence'],a:1,e:`Wood lamp examination of vitiligo shows blue-white accentuation; ultraviolet A illumination enhances contrast between depigmented patches and surrounding pigmented skin.<br><br>Wood lamp also helps detect early hypopigmented lesions and follow treatment response. Tinea versicolor fluoresces yellow-green. Erythrasma fluoresces coral-red. Pseudomonas infection fluoresces green, providing diagnostic clues in clinical practice.<br><br>Yellow fluorescence (option B) characterises tinea versicolor; green fluorescence (option C) indicates Pseudomonas; red fluorescence (option D) suggests erythrasma, none being the blue-white vitiligo accentuation pattern under Wood lamp.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Melasma commonly triggered by',o:['Sun exposure and hormones','Fungal disease','Infection','Trauma'],a:3,e:`Melasma is commonly triggered by sun exposure and hormones; UV radiation activates melanogenesis while estrogens and progesterones (pregnancy, oral contraceptives) increase melanocyte activity.<br><br>Lesions present as symmetric brown macules on cheeks, forehead, upper lip, and chin. Treatment includes strict photoprotection, topical hydroquinone, tretinoin, azelaic acid, and procedural therapies (chemical peels, laser) in resistant cases.<br><br>Fungal disease (option B), infection (option C), and trauma (option D) are not principal melasma triggers, leaving sun and hormonal factors as the established environmental and endogenous drivers of facial hyperpigmentation.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Drug causing hyperpigmentation',o:['Paracetamol','Minocycline','Amoxicillin','Metformin'],a:2,e:`Minocycline causes hyperpigmentation; this tetracycline antibiotic deposits in skin, sclera, teeth, and other tissues producing blue-grey discolouration with prolonged or high-dose use.<br><br>Three patterns: blue-black in scars (type I), blue-grey on shins (type II), and diffuse muddy brown on sun-exposed skin (type III). Discontinuation produces gradual fading over months. Other photosensitisers also induce hyperpigmentation.<br><br>Paracetamol (option A), amoxicillin (option C), and metformin (option D) do not characteristically cause hyperpigmentation, leaving minocycline as the recognised drug-induced cutaneous pigmentation in patients on tetracycline therapy.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Pitting of nails seen in',o:['Vitiligo','Psoriasis','Eczema','Tinea versicolor'],a:0,e:`Pitting of nails is seen in psoriasis; punctate depressions on the nail plate result from psoriatic involvement of the nail matrix producing focal parakeratosis that sloughs leaving pits.<br><br>Other psoriatic nail changes include onycholysis, oil drops, subungual hyperkeratosis, and salmon patches. Up to 50 percent of psoriasis patients have nail involvement, more common in psoriatic arthritis. Alopecia areata also produces fine pits.<br><br>Vitiligo (option A) does not affect nails; eczema (option C) may cause nail dystrophy without classic pitting; tinea versicolor (option D) does not affect nails, none being the principal cause of true pitting clinically.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Clubbing indicates disease of',o:['Lung and heart','Thyroid only','Kidney only','Liver only'],a:1,e:`Clubbing indicates disease of lung and heart; cardiopulmonary causes including bronchiectasis, lung cancer, cyanotic heart disease, and infective endocarditis produce digital clubbing.<br><br>Other associations include inflammatory bowel disease, hepatic cirrhosis, and hyperthyroidism (thyroid acropachy). Mechanism involves platelet-derived growth factor and vascular endothelial growth factor producing connective tissue hyperplasia in distal phalanges over time.<br><br>Thyroid only (option B), kidney only (option C), and liver only (option D) are too narrow as causes; cardiopulmonary disease accounts for the majority of clubbing presentations in clinical practice.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Onychomycosis caused by',o:['Parasite','Bacteria','Dermatophytes','Virus'],a:3,e:`Onychomycosis is caused by dermatophytes; Trichophyton rubrum is the principal cause, invading nail plate and producing the characteristic yellowing, thickening, and crumbling of affected nails.<br><br>Diagnosis by KOH preparation, fungal culture, or PAS staining of nail clippings. Treatment requires prolonged oral antifungals (terbinafine, itraconazole) for 6-12 weeks for fingernails or 12 weeks for toenails. Topical therapy has limited efficacy.<br><br>Parasite (option A), bacteria (option B), and virus (option D) are not the principal organisms causing onychomycosis, leaving dermatophyte fungi as the dominant cause requiring antifungal rather than other therapy.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Koilonychia seen in',o:['Iron deficiency anemia','Hyperthyroidism','Diabetes','Polycythemia'],a:1,e:`Koilonychia is seen in iron deficiency anaemia; spoon-shaped nails with concave surface develop with chronic iron deficiency, often accompanied by glossitis and angular cheilitis.<br><br>Other associations include hereditary forms, nail-patella syndrome, and occupational trauma. Investigation includes complete blood count, iron studies, and ferritin. Iron repletion gradually corrects nail deformity over months as new nail grows.<br><br>Hyperthyroidism (option B) is associated with onycholysis; diabetes (option C) is associated with various nail changes; polycythaemia (option D) is unrelated, leaving iron deficiency as the principal cause of spoon nails clinically.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Androgenetic alopecia due to effect of',o:['DHT on hair follicles','Insulin excess','Cortisol deficiency','Estrogen excess'],a:3,e:`Androgenetic alopecia is due to DHT effect on hair follicles; dihydrotestosterone produced by 5-alpha-reductase from testosterone progressively miniaturises follicles in genetically susceptible scalp areas.<br><br>Male pattern shows bitemporal recession and vertex thinning; female pattern shows diffuse central thinning preserving frontal hairline. Treatment includes topical minoxidil and oral finasteride (males) or anti-androgens (females) for slowing progression.<br><br>Insulin excess (option B), cortisol deficiency (option C), and estrogen excess (option D) are not the principal androgenetic alopecia mechanism, leaving DHT-mediated follicular miniaturisation as the established pathogenesis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Alopecia areata mechanism',o:['Trauma','Fungal infection','Autoimmune attack on hair follicle','Bacterial infection'],a:0,e:`Alopecia areata mechanism is autoimmune attack on hair follicles; T cell-mediated inflammation around anagen follicles disrupts hair growth producing the characteristic well-demarcated patches of hair loss.<br><br>Exclamation mark hairs at lesion edges are characteristic. Associated autoimmune diseases include thyroid disease and vitiligo. Treatment includes topical, intralesional, or systemic corticosteroids; severe disease may benefit from JAK inhibitors recently approved.<br><br>Trauma (option A) causes traumatic alopecia not patchy autoimmune disease; fungal infection (option B) is tinea capitis with scaling; bacterial infection (option D) is folliculitis, none being the alopecia areata mechanism.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Telogen effluvium occurs after',o:['Infection only','Vitamin overdose','Allergy','Physiologic stress'],a:2,e:`Telogen effluvium occurs after physiologic stress; childbirth, surgery, severe illness, or significant weight loss triggers synchronous entry of anagen hairs into telogen phase.<br><br>Diffuse shedding occurs 2-3 months after the inciting event. Hair pull test shows multiple telogen hairs. Recovery is spontaneous over 3-6 months in most cases. Chronic telogen effluvium requires investigation for nutritional or hormonal causes.<br><br>Infection only (option A) is too narrow; vitamin overdose (option B) is uncommon trigger; allergy (option C) is not the typical trigger, leaving physiologic stress as the established cause of acute telogen effluvium.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Tinea capitis causes hair',o:['Excess growth','Curling','Whitening','Broken black dots'],a:0,e:`Tinea capitis causes broken hair shafts producing black dots; ectothrix or endothrix dermatophyte invasion weakens shafts producing breakage at scalp surface and hair loss.<br><br>Trichophyton tonsurans is the main cause of black-dot tinea capitis. Diagnosis by KOH and culture. Treatment requires oral griseofulvin or terbinafine for several weeks, as topical therapy alone cannot eradicate intrafollicular fungus reliably.<br><br>Excess growth (option A), curling (option B), and whitening (option C) are not characteristic tinea capitis hair changes, leaving broken hair shafts and black dots as the principal hair findings in dermatophyte scalp infection.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Primary chancre of syphilis is',o:['Plaque','Painful ulcer','Painless indurated ulcer','Vesicle'],a:1,e:`The primary chancre of syphilis is a painless indurated ulcer; Treponema pallidum produces a clean-based ulcer with rolled edges at the inoculation site, typically resolving in 3-6 weeks.<br><br>Painless regional lymphadenopathy accompanies the chancre. Dark-field microscopy shows spirochetes. Serological tests include non-treponemal (VDRL, RPR) and treponemal (TPHA, FTA-ABS). Untreated infection progresses through secondary, latent, and tertiary stages.<br><br>Plaque (option A) is not chancre morphology; painful ulcer (option C) suggests chancroid (Haemophilus ducreyi); vesicle (option D) suggests herpes, none being the painless indurated chancre of primary syphilis.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Secondary syphilis rash typically involves',o:['Palms and soles','Scalp only','Face only','Nails only'],a:3,e:`Secondary syphilis rash typically involves palms and soles; this generalised non-itchy maculopapular eruption with palmoplantar involvement is highly characteristic of secondary stage spirochaetaemia.<br><br>Other features include condyloma lata, mucous patches, alopecia, fever, and lymphadenopathy. VDRL is positive; FTA-ABS is confirmatory. Treatment with single-dose intramuscular benzathine penicillin clears the infection in this stage.<br><br>Scalp only (option B), face only (option C), and nails only (option D) understate the generalised distribution, with palmoplantar involvement being the diagnostically distinctive feature of secondary syphilis exanthem.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Diagnostic test for syphilis screening',o:['VDRL','Gram stain','KOH','Tzanck smear'],a:2,e:`VDRL is the diagnostic test for syphilis screening; this non-treponemal antibody test detects cardiolipin antibodies produced in response to treponemal infection and tissue damage.<br><br>RPR is similar non-treponemal test. Confirmatory testing requires treponemal-specific tests (TPHA, FTA-ABS). False positives occur in lupus, antiphospholipid syndrome, and pregnancy. Quantitative titres follow treatment response over months.<br><br>Gram stain (option B) is for bacteria; KOH (option C) for fungi; Tzanck smear (option D) for herpes, none being syphilis-specific screening tests in clinical practice for treponemal infection.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Treatment of syphilis drug of choice',o:['Penicillin G','Doxycycline','Azithromycin','Acyclovir'],a:3,e:`Penicillin G is the drug of choice for syphilis treatment; benzathine penicillin G is given as single intramuscular dose for early syphilis or weekly for three weeks in late latent disease.<br><br>Aqueous crystalline penicillin G intravenously treats neurosyphilis. Penicillin allergy requires desensitisation in pregnant women; doxycycline alternative for non-pregnant patients. Jarisch-Herxheimer reaction occurs hours after first dose.<br><br>Doxycycline (option B) is alternative not first-line; azithromycin (option C) has emerging resistance; acyclovir (option D) is antiviral, none being the established first-line antitreponemal therapy across syphilis stages.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Painful grouped vesicles genital area suggests',o:['Chlamydia','Herpes simplex virus','Syphilis','HPV'],a:0,e:`Painful grouped vesicles in the genital area suggest herpes simplex virus; HSV-2 is the principal genital pathogen producing recurrent vesicular outbreaks at the same anatomic site over years.<br><br>Treatment with oral acyclovir, valacyclovir, or famciclovir reduces severity and duration. Suppressive therapy decreases recurrence frequency. PCR is most sensitive diagnostic test. Latency in sacral dorsal root ganglia underlies recurrent disease pattern.<br><br>Chlamydia (option A) causes urethritis and cervicitis without vesicles; syphilis (option C) presents with painless indurated chancre; HPV (option D) causes warts, none being the herpetic vesicular pattern.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Genital warts caused by',o:['Treponema','Candida','HSV','HPV 6,11'],a:2,e:`Genital warts are caused by HPV types 6 and 11; these low-risk human papillomavirus strains produce benign verrucous papules and cauliflower-like masses on anogenital skin and mucosa.<br><br>HPV-16 and HPV-18 are oncogenic types associated with cervical, anal, and oropharyngeal cancers. HPV vaccination prevents infection with the major oncogenic and wart-causing strains. Treatment includes podophyllotoxin, imiquimod, cryotherapy, surgery.<br><br>Treponema (option A) causes syphilis; Candida (option B) causes thrush; HSV (option C) causes herpes vesicles, none being the human papillomavirus aetiology of genital warts in sexually active adults.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Donovanosis characterized by',o:['Vesicles','Plaques','Nodules','Beefy red painless ulcers'],a:1,e:`Donovanosis is characterised by beefy red painless ulcers; Klebsiella granulomatis produces slowly progressive painless genital ulceration that bleeds easily on contact with friable granulation tissue surface.<br><br>Donovan bodies (intracellular organisms in macrophages) on tissue smear or biopsy confirm diagnosis. Treatment with doxycycline, azithromycin, or trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole for 3 weeks or until healed produces resolution. Common in tropical regions.<br><br>Vesicles (option A) are not donovanosis morphology; plaques (option B) and nodules (option C) understate the characteristic ulcerative lesions, leaving beefy red painless friable ulcers as defining donovanosis presentation.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Chancroid caused by',o:['Haemophilus ducreyi','HSV','HPV','Treponema pallidum'],a:3,e:`Chancroid is caused by Haemophilus ducreyi; this Gram-negative coccobacillus produces painful genital ulcers with ragged undermined edges and tender suppurative inguinal lymphadenopathy.<br><br>Diagnosis by Gram stain showing school-of-fish arrangement, culture on selective media, or PCR. Treatment with single-dose ceftriaxone, oral azithromycin, or 7 days of erythromycin produces resolution. Common in developing countries.<br><br>HSV (option B) causes painful vesicles not ulcers; HPV (option C) causes warts; Treponema pallidum (option D) causes painless syphilitic chancre, all distinct from the painful Haemophilus ducreyi chancroid lesions.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'Lymphogranuloma venereum caused by',o:['Gonorrhea','HSV','Syphilis','Chlamydia trachomatis L1-3'],a:0,e:`Lymphogranuloma venereum is caused by Chlamydia trachomatis serovars L1, L2, L3; these invasive serovars produce primary genital lesion followed by tender suppurative inguinal lymphadenopathy (groove sign).<br><br>Late stage may produce rectal stricture and lymphatic obstruction with elephantiasis. Diagnosis by serology and PCR for chlamydial DNA. Treatment with doxycycline 100 mg twice daily for 21 days resolves infection in most patients.<br><br>Gonorrhoea (option A) is Neisseria gonorrhoeae; HSV (option B) causes herpes vesicles; syphilis (option C) is treponemal, none being the chlamydial lymphogranuloma venereum aetiology specifically in tropical regions.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'First stage HIV skin manifestation',o:['Alopecia','Vitiligo','Psoriasis','Maculopapular rash'],a:2,e:`First-stage HIV skin manifestation is maculopapular rash; primary HIV infection produces a non-specific morbilliform eruption similar to other viral exanthems with fever and lymphadenopathy.<br><br>Acute retroviral syndrome includes fever, fatigue, pharyngitis, lymphadenopathy, and rash 2-4 weeks after exposure. HIV PCR is positive before antibody seroconversion. Diagnosis enables early antiretroviral therapy with improved long-term outcomes.<br><br>Alopecia (option A) is later manifestation; vitiligo (option B) is autoimmune unrelated to acute HIV; psoriasis (option C) may worsen with HIV but is not initial manifestation, leaving morbilliform rash as the early skin finding.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Kaposi sarcoma associated virus',o:['HHV-8','HPV','EBV','HSV-1'],a:1,e:`Kaposi sarcoma is associated with HHV-8; human herpesvirus 8 (Kaposi sarcoma-associated herpesvirus) drives endothelial cell transformation producing characteristic violaceous patches, plaques, and nodules.<br><br>Classic, endemic (African), iatrogenic (transplant), and AIDS-associated forms differ in epidemiology. AIDS-related disease responds to antiretroviral therapy with immune reconstitution. Local and systemic chemotherapy treats extensive or visceral disease in some patients.<br><br>HPV (option B) causes warts and cervical cancer; EBV (option C) causes lymphomas; HSV-1 (option D) causes orolabial herpes, none being the principal viral aetiology of Kaposi sarcoma in any epidemiological setting.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient presents with flaccid blisters, erosions in mouth, positive Nikolsky sign. Diagnosis',o:['Bullous pemphigoid','Pemphigus vulgaris','Impetigo','Dermatitis herpetiformis'],a:0,e:`Flaccid blisters with mouth erosions and positive Nikolsky sign indicate pemphigus vulgaris; autoantibodies against desmoglein-3 disrupt desmosomal adhesion producing intraepidermal acantholytic blistering.<br><br>Direct immunofluorescence shows IgG deposition in fishnet pattern around keratinocytes. Mortality untreated reaches 75 percent. Treatment with systemic corticosteroids, immunosuppressants, and rituximab now produces good outcomes in most patients clinically.<br><br>Bullous pemphigoid (option A) shows tense bullae with negative Nikolsky; impetigo (option C) is bacterial superficial; dermatitis herpetiformis (option D) shows grouped vesicles, none matching the flaccid acantholytic pemphigus pattern.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'An elderly patient has tense bullae on trunk, negative Nikolsky sign. Diagnosis',o:['Pemphigus vulgaris','TEN','SJS','Bullous pemphigoid'],a:1,e:`Tense bullae on trunk in elderly patient with negative Nikolsky sign indicate bullous pemphigoid; autoantibodies against hemidesmosome proteins BP180 and BP230 produce tense subepidermal blisters.<br><br>Direct immunofluorescence shows linear IgG and C3 deposition along basement membrane. Mortality is lower than pemphigus vulgaris. Treatment includes systemic corticosteroids, steroid-sparing immunosuppressants, and rituximab in refractory disease.<br><br>Pemphigus vulgaris (option A) features flaccid blisters with positive Nikolsky; TEN (option B) is acute drug-induced epidermal detachment; SJS (option C) overlaps TEN, all distinct from chronic bullous pemphigoid in elderly.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A young adult with intensely itchy grouped vesicles on elbows and gluten intolerance. Diagnosis',o:['Eczema','Bullous pemphigoid','Dermatitis herpetiformis','Pemphigus'],a:3,e:`Itchy grouped vesicles on elbows with gluten intolerance indicate dermatitis herpetiformis; the cutaneous manifestation of celiac disease produces intensely pruritic grouped papulovesicles on extensor surfaces.<br><br>Granular IgA deposition in dermal papillae on direct immunofluorescence is diagnostic. Tissue transglutaminase autoantibodies link skin and gut disease. Treatment with strict gluten-free diet alongside dapsone produces relief and disease control.<br><br>Eczema (option A) is poorly demarcated and pruritic without grouped vesicles; bullous pemphigoid (option B) is in elderly with tense bullae; pemphigus (option D) features mucosal involvement, distinct entities.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman with symmetrical depigmented patches on hands accentuated under Wood lamp. Management first step',o:['Antifungal','Antibiotics','Antiviral','Topical steroids or tacrolimus'],a:2,e:`Symmetrical depigmented patches on hands accentuated under Wood lamp indicate vitiligo; first-line treatment includes topical corticosteroids or tacrolimus to suppress autoimmune melanocyte destruction.<br><br>Combination with phototherapy improves response. Stable depigmented patches in cosmetically sensitive areas may benefit from melanocyte transplantation. Wood lamp examination both confirms diagnosis and monitors treatment response over months of therapy.<br><br>Antifungal (option A) treats fungal infection; antibiotics (option B) treat bacterial; antiviral (option C) treats viral infection, none being therapeutic for autoimmune vitiligo in symmetric distribution.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'A man with spoon shaped nails and fatigue. Investigation most relevant',o:['LFT','Blood sugar','Serum ferritin','Thyroid test'],a:1,e:`Spoon-shaped nails with fatigue most relevantly investigated by serum ferritin; koilonychia with fatigue suggests iron deficiency anaemia, and ferritin is the most sensitive iron storage indicator.<br><br>Complete blood count, iron studies (serum iron, TIBC, transferrin saturation), and ferritin together evaluate iron deficiency. Investigation of cause includes gastrointestinal evaluation in adults to exclude occult bleeding or malabsorption from coeliac disease.<br><br>LFT (option A) assesses liver; blood sugar (option B) screens diabetes; thyroid test (option D) screens thyroid disease, none being the principal investigation for koilonychia with fatigue suggesting iron deficiency.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'A patchy non scarring hair loss with exclamation mark hairs suggests',o:['Tinea capitis','Telogen effluvium','Alopecia areata','Trichotillomania'],a:3,e:`Patchy non-scarring hair loss with exclamation mark hairs suggests alopecia areata; T cell-mediated autoimmune attack on anagen follicles produces well-demarcated patches with characteristic short tapered hairs.<br><br>Pull test at active edges yields anagen hairs. Associated autoimmune diseases include thyroid disease and vitiligo. Treatment includes topical, intralesional, or systemic corticosteroids; severe disease may benefit from JAK inhibitors recently approved.<br><br>Tinea capitis (option A) shows scaling and broken hair shafts; telogen effluvium (option B) is diffuse; trichotillomania (option D) shows irregular borders with hairs of varying lengths, none matching exclamation mark pattern.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with multiple sexual partners presents painless ulcer and positive VDRL. Management',o:['Acyclovir','Benzathine penicillin','Steroids','Fluconazole'],a:0,e:`Multiple sexual partners with painless ulcer and positive VDRL warrants benzathine penicillin treatment; primary syphilis treatment requires single-dose intramuscular benzathine penicillin G 2.4 million units.<br><br>Confirmatory treponemal testing (TPHA, FTA-ABS) supports diagnosis. Quantitative VDRL titres followed at 6 and 12 months assess treatment response. Sexual partners require evaluation and presumptive treatment to prevent ongoing transmission community-wide.<br><br>Acyclovir (option A) is for herpes; steroids (option C) are inappropriate for active infection; fluconazole (option D) is antifungal, none being the established treatment for primary syphilis with positive VDRL.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'Painful genital ulcer with tender lymph nodes and purulent base. Diagnosis',o:['Chancroid','HSV','LGV','Syphilis'],a:2,e:`Painful genital ulcer with tender lymph nodes and purulent base suggests chancroid; Haemophilus ducreyi produces deep ulcers with ragged edges and suppurative inguinal lymphadenopathy classically.<br><br>Single-dose ceftriaxone, oral azithromycin, or 7 days of erythromycin treats chancroid effectively. Common in developing countries. Co-infection with HIV warrants screening; chancroid facilitates HIV transmission through ulcerated mucosa significantly clinically.<br><br>Chancroid (option A) is the diagnosis being asked though appears as option here; HSV (option B) shows grouped vesicles; syphilis (option D) is painless indurated, all distinct from the painful purulent chancroid.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'HIV patient develops violaceous plaques on skin and oral mucosa. Cause',o:['Drug rash','Kaposi sarcoma','Tinea','Psoriasis'],a:0,e:`HIV patient with violaceous plaques on skin and oral mucosa likely has Kaposi sarcoma; HHV-8 drives endothelial cell transformation producing violaceous patches, plaques, and nodules on skin and mucous membranes.<br><br>AIDS-associated Kaposi sarcoma responds to antiretroviral therapy with immune reconstitution in most cases. Local radiotherapy and systemic chemotherapy treat extensive cutaneous, lymphatic, or visceral disease in some patients with advanced presentation.<br><br>Drug rash (option B) is morbilliform; tinea (option C) shows scaling annular lesions; psoriasis (option D) has silvery scale, none matching the violaceous KS plaques in immunocompromised patients clinically.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman with diffuse hair shedding 3 months after childbirth. Diagnosis',o:['Tinea capitis','Alopecia areata','Telogen effluvium','Androgenetic alopecia'],a:3,e:`Diffuse hair shedding 3 months after childbirth indicates telogen effluvium; postpartum hormonal changes synchronise anagen hairs into telogen producing diffuse shedding 2-3 months after the inciting event.<br><br>Hair pull test shows multiple telogen hairs. Recovery is spontaneous over 6-12 months as hairs re-enter anagen. Reassurance and observation are appropriate; no specific treatment is required for this self-limiting physiological pattern.<br><br>Tinea capitis (option A) shows patchy scaling; alopecia areata (option B) is patchy not diffuse; androgenetic alopecia (option D) is gradual progressive miniaturisation, none matching the postpartum diffuse pattern.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A 30-year-old presents with recurrent oral erosions and flaccid bullae over trunk, histology shows acantholysis above basal layer. Most specific test',o:['Gram stain','Direct immunofluorescence IgG intercellular','KOH mount','PAS stain'],a:2,e:`Recurrent oral erosions with flaccid bullae and acantholysis above basal layer specifically diagnosed by direct immunofluorescence showing IgG intercellular pattern; this fishnet pattern is characteristic of pemphigus vulgaris.<br><br>Anti-desmoglein-3 antibodies confirm diagnosis on serum testing. Histology shows suprabasal acantholysis. Treatment with systemic corticosteroids, immunosuppressants, and rituximab now produces good outcomes for this previously frequently fatal autoimmune blistering disease.<br><br>Gram stain (option A) is for bacterial infection; KOH mount (option C) is for fungi; PAS stain (option D) is for fungi and basement membrane, none being specific for pemphigus diagnosis at protein level.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with chronic pruritic plaques over elbows improves on gluten free diet. Mechanism',o:['IgG basement membrane','Fungal hypersensitivity','IgA deposition in dermal papillae','Complement deficiency'],a:1,e:`Chronic pruritic plaques over elbows improving on gluten-free diet have IgA deposition in dermal papillae; this autoimmune mechanism characterises dermatitis herpetiformis as cutaneous celiac disease manifestation.<br><br>Granular IgA on direct immunofluorescence is diagnostic. Tissue transglutaminase autoantibodies link skin and gut disease. Strict gluten-free diet allows reduction or discontinuation of dapsone over 6-24 months in compliant patients clinically.<br><br>IgG basement membrane (option A) is bullous pemphigoid; fungal hypersensitivity (option B) is dermatophytid; complement deficiency (option D) causes other diseases, none being dermatitis herpetiformis mechanism specifically.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A 22-year-old woman presents with irregular hyperpigmented facial patches worsening in pregnancy. Best management',o:['Oral antibiotics','Steroids injection','Oral antivirals','Sunscreen and hydroquinone'],a:0,e:`Irregular hyperpigmented facial patches worsening in pregnancy indicate melasma best managed with sunscreen and hydroquinone; strict photoprotection combined with topical depigmenting agents is foundational management.<br><br>Triple combination cream (hydroquinone, tretinoin, fluocinolone) is highly effective. Tranexamic acid orally is alternative for resistant cases. Procedural therapies (chemical peels, laser) supplement topical treatment but require careful patient selection to avoid post-inflammatory hyperpigmentation.<br><br>Oral antibiotics (option A) treat infection; steroids injection (option B) is not for melasma; oral antivirals (option C) treat viral infection, none being effective melasma therapy in pregnancy-related hyperpigmentation.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'A nail plate separates from nail bed in hyperthyroidism. Term',o:['Onycholysis','Beau lines','Clubbing','Koilonychia'],a:1,e:`Nail plate separation from nail bed in hyperthyroidism is termed onycholysis; thyroid hormone excess produces this distal nail detachment, creating the characteristic Plummer nail pattern in thyrotoxicosis.<br><br>Other onycholysis causes include trauma, psoriasis, fungal infection, and contact reactions to nail products. Treatment of underlying hyperthyroidism corrects the nail change over months as new nail grows out from matrix.<br><br>Beau lines (option B) are transverse depressions from systemic illness; clubbing (option C) is bulbous distal phalanx swelling; koilonychia (option D) is spoon-shape from iron deficiency, all distinct from onycholysis.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with patterned hair loss and miniaturized follicles. Drug therapy',o:['Dapsone','Finasteride','Acyclovir','Methotrexate'],a:3,e:`Patterned hair loss with miniaturised follicles suggests androgenetic alopecia; finasteride blocks 5-alpha-reductase, reducing dihydrotestosterone and slowing follicular miniaturisation in male patients.<br><br>Topical minoxidil also slows progression. Female pattern responds less consistently to finasteride; spironolactone or other anti-androgens are alternatives. Treatment requires sustained use; benefits are lost on discontinuation as androgenetic process resumes.<br><br>Dapsone (option A) is for dermatitis herpetiformis; acyclovir (option C) is antiviral; methotrexate (option D) is for severe psoriasis or other inflammatory disease, none treating androgenetic follicular miniaturisation.<br><br><em>(Davidson's Principles and Practice of Medicine)</em>`},
    {q:'A man presents with painless genital ulcer followed weeks later by generalized rash involving palms and soles. Stage',o:['Primary syphilis','Secondary syphilis','Latent syphilis','Tertiary syphilis'],a:2,e:`Painless genital ulcer followed weeks later by generalised palmoplantar rash indicates secondary syphilis; the spirochaetaemic stage features generalised maculopapular rash characteristically involving palms and soles.<br><br>Other features include condyloma lata, mucous patches, alopecia, fever, and lymphadenopathy. VDRL is positive; FTA-ABS is confirmatory. Treatment with single-dose intramuscular benzathine penicillin clears the infection in this stage clinically.<br><br>Primary syphilis (option A) is the chancre alone; latent syphilis (option C) is asymptomatic seroreactivity; tertiary syphilis (option D) has gummas and neurosyphilis, all distinct from the secondary spirochaetaemic rash.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'HIV positive patient presents with multiple pearly papules with central umbilication in genital area. Cause',o:['Molluscum contagiosum','HPV','Candida','HSV'],a:1,e:`HIV-positive patient with multiple pearly umbilicated papules in genital area has molluscum contagiosum; this poxvirus infection produces 2-5 mm flesh-coloured papules with central depression, often more numerous and persistent in immunosuppression.<br><br>Treatment includes cryotherapy, curettage, or topical agents. Antiretroviral therapy with immune reconstitution often produces resolution. HIV patients may have more lesions, atypical morphology, and slower response to standard treatments.<br><br>HPV (option B) causes warts not umbilicated; Candida (option C) causes plaques; HSV (option D) causes vesicles, none matching the umbilicated molluscum morphology in HIV-positive genital lesions.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A young male with painful grouped vesicles recurrent at same site genital region. Latency location of virus',o:['Skin','Sacral dorsal root ganglion','Blood','Spinal cord'],a:2,e:`Painful grouped vesicles recurrent at the same genital site indicate HSV with virus latency in sacral dorsal root ganglion; HSV-2 establishes latency in sacral ganglia after primary infection with subsequent reactivations.<br><br>Recurrences trigger by stress, illness, or immunosuppression. Treatment with oral acyclovir, valacyclovir, or famciclovir reduces severity and duration. Suppressive therapy decreases recurrence frequency. PCR is most sensitive diagnostic test.<br><br>Skin (option A) is not the latency site; blood (option C) does not harbour latent HSV; spinal cord (option D) is not the latency site, leaving sacral dorsal root ganglion as the established HSV-2 latency reservoir.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient develops sudden diffuse epidermal detachment after drug exposure, positive Nikolsky sign, mucosal erosions. Diagnosis',o:['Erythema multiforme minor','Toxic epidermal necrolysis','Pemphigus vulgaris','Bullous pemphigoid'],a:0,e:`Sudden diffuse epidermal detachment after drug exposure with positive Nikolsky and mucosal erosions indicates toxic epidermal necrolysis; TEN involves over 30 percent body surface area with full-thickness epidermal necrosis.<br><br>Stevens-Johnson syndrome involves under 10 percent BSA. Common drug triggers include sulfonamides, anticonvulsants, allopurinol, and NSAIDs. Treatment in burn unit with supportive care; cyclosporine or IVIG show benefit. Mortality reaches 30 percent in severe cases.<br><br>Erythema multiforme minor (option A) is more limited; pemphigus vulgaris (option C) is autoimmune chronic; bullous pemphigoid (option D) is chronic in elderly, all distinct from the acute drug-induced TEN.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`},
    {q:'A sexually active patient presents with beefy red painless genital ulcer bleeding on touch and Donovan bodies on smear. Diagnosis',o:['Granuloma inguinale','Syphilis','Herpes','Chancroid'],a:3,e:`Beefy red painless genital ulcer with bleeding and Donovan bodies indicates granuloma inguinale (donovanosis); Klebsiella granulomatis produces the characteristic friable ulcerating lesion with Donovan bodies on smear.<br><br>Treatment with doxycycline, azithromycin, or trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole for 3 weeks or until healed produces resolution. Common in tropical regions. Sexual partners require examination and treatment to prevent ongoing transmission within sexual networks.<br><br>Chancroid (option B) is painful with purulent base; syphilis (option C) chancre is painless but indurated without Donovan bodies; herpes (option D) shows vesicles, none being the Donovan body-positive donovanosis lesion.<br><br><em>(First Aid for USMLE Step 1)</em>`}
  ];
})();